\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Could you tell me your name and present address please?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well - full name? My full name's Bessie Vivian Angove.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And your present address?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Crevets. {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname address}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname Street}}Crane Road{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}. Camborne.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What year were you married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Gracious me. Wait a minute. 1929.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 The year you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 1901.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Where were you born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I was born at - Crevets Farm, Nancegollan. In the parish of Breage.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How many years did you live in the house where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I must have lived in the house there fifty-four or five years, where I was born.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 After you were married as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes
, see my - my - mother died when I was - about twenty-one. Then I was the - oldest of the family. And - I couldn't make up my mind to - leave the family, my - my youngest brother can't remember his mother at all. And the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You looked after him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes. And you see, then I stayed at home and - looked after the family. And - after my father died - my brother - after a year or two he decided to - get married. And - that's why we - moved from the farm over to Nancegollan. But the children were born - a
ll over on the - farm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You moved to Nancegollan village then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Moved to Nancegollan village then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How long did you live there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 About eleven years I think. In the village.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Then where did you next move?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Here, Camborne then, we moved to Comborne, been - we've been here - five years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Why did you make the move to Camborne?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well I suppose the - main reason was because our daughter was - here working. Before - the other - her other sister was here working, and - she 
decided to get married and go to Plymouth, and our eldest daughter - decided to come from Plymouth to Camborne, to take the job at Camborne you see, and - of course after living in Plymouth - she didn't want to come to Nancegollan and a little village lik
e that, she said she wouldn't come to Nancegollan to live so - we decided well we'll go to Camborne. And a good job we did now really, 'cos - I mean no transport in any of these villages hardly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How many brothers and sisters did you have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 One sister, three brothers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What place were they in the family, who was the next after you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 My sister. My sister was the next.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And she was a year younger than you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 She was one year younger than - I was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How old was the next one, how much younger than her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well the next one would be about four years younger and then -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What was his name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Sidney George.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 He was born in 1906?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, I think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And John Peter, he was the next one, five years between?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Five years, 1911 I think he would be.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And the youngest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 1916.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And that was James Howard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 James Howard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How old was your father when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Thirty - two. Thirty-two years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Where did he come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 He came from Nancegollan.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And his occupation? What did he do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well his - his - he was on a little smallholding with his father and - when the railway - was put from - Gwinear Road to Helston, he worked on the railway. And then he moved from - there over
 to - from Nancegollan over to Crevets on the - in the Breage parish you see, on a bigger place and - of course that - took up all his time then, farming.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 So he left the railway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well he was only working on the railway - laying rails you know, a
s the work - the - the cutting and that kind when they put the railway in - that employed quite a few people at that time on the railway there to - make the - railway.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What did he actually do then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well I suppose really labouring.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Do you know what he did before that, before working on the railway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well - at home with his father on this - smallholding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did he do any casual or part time jobs apart from his work, on the railway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 He didn't take up farming until he left the railway and bought the smallholding?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well I think that was like a lot of people did in they times - some went to mine to help to supplement and some went on the railway and did the little smallholding on - out of core job really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 He started that while he was on the railway?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Do you remember your father ever being out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How old was your mother when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 She was twenty-five.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Where did she come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 She came from a little place - called Trenwheal, it's in the - Breage Parish.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was it a village or a hamlet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Oh a hamlet, yes, a hamlet, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did she have any job before she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 On - she was living with an aunt before - tending this aunt.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did she do any work after she was married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. Full time employment - by that time. Children started coming.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How many rooms in the house at Crevets Farm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 It was an old house, cob walls. Three bedrooms. Four rooms downstairs. Quite a big - quit
e a big kitchen. An old fashioned - range, called a slab then. Had a fringle beside of it, and a spence beside the fringle, if you know what that is.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Could you tell me about a spence, I know what a fringle is, that's a little fireplace.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, whe
re they keep the sticks and the boiler and - a fringle is - the fringle - the spence was where you kept your brushes and pots and pans.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Is that under the stairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. Beside the fringle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 So of these four downstairs rooms you had a big kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Big kitchen, and back kitchen, dairy, and - front room. The parlour.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did anyone else besides your parents and brothers and sister live in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. Grandmother used to come up - every - Monday, and stay until Wednesday to help my mother - to do the washing and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid927206\charrsid348800 \endash }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800  butter}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid927206\charrsid348800 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
making and - she would give her a hand see, to help her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Where did she live?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 She lived at Trenwheal, she used to walk up every Monday and stay until Wednesday to - help - mother. See 'cos in they - in they
 days - it was altogether different, the - you had to carry your water.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Where did you carry it from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
The - in the winter time we had rain water but in the - summertime we had to go a mile and a half from Chynhale with the horse and barrel to bring home the water. For we were making butter see in the summertime - four - four times a - a week there then.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you have any lodgers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No room for lodgers. No room for lodgers. The - the only time - I remember - having lodgers was - when we had
 a threshing machine - and the three men that came with the threshing machine, once or twice we had to put them - up. 'Cos - rather crowded like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Where would they normally stay if you didn't put them up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Out at the pub.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 That would be in the harvest time would it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did mother ever pay anyone to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
No. No. Grandma used to come and give her a hand and - The washing was done at home then, what sort of apparatus was the washing done with We had - boiler, well 
call it copper I suppose up in the wash - wash house our of doors, and we children had to pick sticks Saturdays - for to - boil up the water for Mondays. And - we had to carry all the water - for washing in the summertime. And after - she finished washing
 quite often - father would be killing three pigs, Mondays, three pigs again Fridays, or Thursdays, and we had to carry - water and sticks. That was children'}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid927206\charrsid348800 s job to be car - carrying furze}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800  and sticks to keep the fire going to boil all this water.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Where would you get the fur}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid927206\charrsid348800 z}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 e and sticks from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well - no, they used to - part of the time - in the wintertime - or I suppose spring time, they would be cut - cut the fur}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid927206\charrsid348800 ze}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800  out the fields, bring it in, trimming hedges and that, never nothing was}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid927206\charrsid348800 ted, bri
ng in - all their - furz}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 e and sticks and then cart them out in the rick - rick them out in the mow}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid927206\charrsid348800 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 hay. And then we'd cart it from the mow}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid927206\charrsid348800 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
hay, for the - up to the wash house. And all washing by hand then. You know, with the - rubbing board - there. Quite often I'd come home from school on Monday and - with butter}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid927206\charrsid348800 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 making Mondays too and washing my mother hadn't finished washing because - by time she made butter and - done the washing - for - children, because children were - starched pinafores and - all whi
te underclothes it was - pile of children}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid927206\charrsid348800 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 s washing in they day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And they would be boiled in this copper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Boil in this great - big copper there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Could you get any water apart from this long distance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Only rain - rain water, there's no stream nearby, rainwater. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And none of that in the summer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, summertime - everything - all tanks were dry and - have to carry it in Chynhale.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did mother or father mend or make any of the family's clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Oh yes. Yes. I don't remember going to a dressmaker until we - grew up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Mother would make the clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes, and - mother's sister sometimes too, her - she would - help, she's quite handy with her needle and she made our - clothes. And all the knitting, knitting 
stockings in they days. Of course grandma used to help to do that too. All knitted stockings. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Mother had a sewing machine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What about shoes, where did you get shoes in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well we used to go to Helston - for them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you wear shoes or boots?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I don't ever remember wearing boots.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were the clothes always new or were they ever second}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid927206\charrsid348800  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 hand?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Oh - I think they were always new unless some of your relatives - passed on anything - to them like the childr
en did of any - of any time there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Your clothes would be passed on to your sister?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And your brothers one from the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was there any particular time for buying new clothes in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Wintertime. Harvest - Helston Harvest Fair we always went to - Helston Harvest Fair, and we always had new clothes for winter. In -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What time of the year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 September. September. That was quite a outing. Looked forward to that - there - in a horse and trap going off
 - there and - but we always made this the point of when you had new clothes, in - in the - spring, we would have something again for - summer. Then - then - I remember - walking to Nancegollan station to catch the train - to go to Helston. To get new clo
t
hes. I - and what we were going to have I don't know but I know on the way - they'd been carrying coal from Nancegollan station to Breage, and there was a lot of coal on the roads, and mother said - 'cos grandmother's living at Nancegollan at that time, s
h
e said, here, we must pick that up and carry that into grandma. And because we wasted the time picking - up - the coal we missed this train, we were set out to go to Camborne you see, we missed this train, well, she said, never mind, we'll go to Helston i
nstead. Well to go to Camborne was some outing in they days. And we went to Helsto}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid927206\charrsid348800 n instead. And brought some gre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
y material, and I never liked it, but - we were so disappointed because we didn't get to - Camborne, we never liked the material, never liked the old clothes and everything.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Do you remember any special time in the spring for buying these summer clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 During the - the Easter time. I never went to Flora until I was sixteen years of age, because that wasn't the thing. It was only fools
 that went to Flora. We spent Flora Day - most of the day picking stones in the fields.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 It was a school holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 It was a school holiday but - we never went to Flora because - they was a silly lot that - went to Helston Flora. I'm certain me fat
her wouldn't - we couldn't go unless he drove the horse and trap, and - he wasn't - never had no time for that, my goodness, go Helston Flora. But we spent the day - picking stones. Then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Clearing them from the fields?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Clearing them from the field, yes, they used to do it - in they days, they don't now. They leave the stones there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Do you remember anything about buying shoes, you'd normally go to Helston for those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 We always went to Helston - anything we - wanted, in the clothing line, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did father help mother with any of the jobs in the house, like cleaning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, he never - did that. Took him all his time to do - outdoor work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What about fires, would he ever do any kindling or lighting the fires?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. That w
asn't the woman - that wasn't the man's job. It was the woman to do - do it. In they days men didn't help their husbands a lot, men didn't help their wives a lot did they.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What about any house decorating or repairs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Mother - would do that. Yes. Yes, mother would do that. 'Cos the - dairy, the back kitchen, that was all limed - there. In they days. And -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Your mother would do it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. And we had no - indoor sanitation. Outside toilet across the - yard there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 That would be a pit closet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Somebody would have to clear that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. That - that was father's job. That was the father's job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What about any improvements to the house, do you ever remember anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Not - not when we were small
, because - it was a rented farm then, and after the - war - first war - my father bought it and then he did some improvements on it. He - new windows, doors and shingled the front. New floors.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 That was after the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 That was after the war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 When you were young at home before and during the war, did he ever find time to read to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well - I - not read to us, he used to read quite a bit, he was quite - oh could - discuss and - very well, take a service at chapel and that kind of thing,
 and - used to read quite - quite a bit - the papers, have the daily paper and - Methodist Recorder he used to take up, or British Weekly then I think it was called. He used to read that and - sometimes - after we had Sunday school prizes - they would rea
d - perhaps a story but then I - I - we could always read ourselves as far as I remember. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did he ever tell you stories?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well I don't know that he had much - a lot of time for that it seemed. He was up early in the morning, and when we were g
one to school - we were away to school all day, because it was quite a way. And the time we came home he was - evening work to do and - we went to bed quite early, that - I don't remember him telling much - much stories really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did he ever have time or occasion to take you out without mother like for walks or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
No, never had no time to - go out for - walks, because - chapel took up - most of her time, you know, it was coming and going to - to chapel when we were - young. That took up - most of his time. That was only source of entertainment. In they days.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You would all go then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes. Well - mother wouldn't be able to go because she was quite often along with the - small ones, but as soon as they got any age we - always - father was - would take - take us there, yes, he was organist there for - lots of years and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Which chapel was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Nancegollan. And - in the summertime - mother would be able to go, but it was - was walking a mile and a half. Sundays was a 
very busy day. Really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How often did you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Three times. Morning - yes, mornings, back again, afternoon Sunday school, evening again, well - I don't think we children went, not in the wintertime, in the evening, but he would always - go because
 he was boun to go, really, because he was - organist there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you say he took the service?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Does that mean he was a local preacher?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, he wasn't a local preacher, but if the preacher didn't turn up - he could - always take this - the service there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Then he would act as organist?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And take the service?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Oh well, when we come to any age - I would act as organist and he'd take the preachering. And I can remember once - my brother - youngest brother coming 
home saying, well we done it all today didn't we? He said, daddy took the service, and Bessie played, and I took up the collection. And then we used to have the - preacher over to dinner you see. That was the - regular thing, and he would drive up from do
w
n to Hayle in a little pony jingle. They'd be planned different places and Nancegollan was the - last place on the - that side you see and the pony would be kept there, and - then - they would bring over the pony - and jingle and drive home to our place q
uite often you see for dinner, that was quite a outing for - for they people.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And company I suppose for you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Oh we used to love - we used - yes, we liked that, yes, the ride on the pony jingle and - that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 With the preacher?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I suppose father would never have any time to help to bath or put you to bed or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Very rare occasions that mother went out of a evening and left him home - to put we to bed there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 If she did go what would that be, to sort of visit her mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well, no, perhaps there might have been a - entertainment or anything and - she would - go over occasionally.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 At chapel that would be would it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, at the chapel.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you have any tasks that you had to carry out regularly at home to help mother and father, apart from what you've told me?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Some - Saturdays - one job was - to wash the dish}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid927206\charrsid348800 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 clothes and the dusters. And - with so much difference ages there was seemed to be always the baby to tend. I was - what - say I
 was nine or ten when - the second one was born, my second brother, and always - wanted - before I go to school, look sharp, come down and dress the baby before you go. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you do any other little tasks for the little ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well keep them e
mployed - and amuse them, and that, but then - we went to school and that was a - mile and a half to go. I went to school when I was about two and a half, because the - one that was teaching down school was our neighbour and always anxious to take me to s
chool. So I was sent off to school, she put me in the pushchair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you continue to do these little tasks at home after you left}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid927206\charrsid348800  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 When I - was fourteen, I should have very much liked to have - stayed on to school and gone to the - seconda
ry school. But there was another baby expected then, my youngest brother was on the way, and instead of going to - stay on to school, I was sent to a dairy school for three courses instead, to learn to work -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Where was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 The dairy school was
 - at Chynhale, at - an old milk factory, then. And they had a - a course there for - couple of years, and - round about six weeks, six or eight weeks. Had three spells there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Who was that run by?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 The County Council. Sponsored it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did the younger children have any little jobs to do to help the older ones?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
No, I think they were playing mostly. 'Cos the boys would be out with father quite often when they got to any age at all, except my youngest brother, and he was - generally around with me. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you have any little tasks to do like helping them with their dressing or eating?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, they looked after themselves pretty well once they was dressed in the morning. They amused theirselves very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time in your schooldays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 We always went to bed - very good time. Seven or eight o'clock and that was the - latest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did mother or anyone else put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, we - I think we put ourselves to bed mostly. We were - it w
as an old house and there was two great - chimneys - at each end in - inside, one had a plat on it, you could get up on it to stand you see and we used to go to bed and then we would stand up on this plat and we'd spring off on the bed you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 This is in the bedroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
This is in the bedroom, yes. And we looked in - in - under our - our bed - there was a little hole in the floor, not so big as that - and we always suspicious they's doing something underneath you see, we would cr}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid927206\charrsid348800 a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 wl in under the be
d to look to see what - they was having, is anything suspicious going on and then they would know that we were doing something and then you could hear the poker knock to the - ceiling, get in that bed.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 This was a little hole made by a knot in the wood?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You don't ever remember anyone putting you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, don't remember anyone putting me to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you share the bedroom or bed with anyone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 My sister and I.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You had three bedrooms, did that mean that you and your sister had one room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And the boys one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Boys in other ones, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What room did you bath in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 In the - win}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid927206\charrsid348800 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
ertime we bathed in the back kitchen. In the summertime, it was up in the wash house. Light the furnace fire up and - bath that way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How often did this happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Oh we were bathed - once - once a week in the wintertime.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Most families would have a once a week bath and the clean clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Usually a Friday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Where did the family have their meals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 In the kitchen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were there ever any occasions when you ate in another room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Harvest time. Threshing days. Back kitchen too then. But - in the summertime it was very hot with the fire in the kitchen, we wo
uld have it out in the back kitchen where it was cold when it was very hot. But the kitchen was a big kitchen. Great big - kitchen table, that would - would - twelve or fourteen easy.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 So even with harvest time that would cater for most of you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes. Most of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was the cooking done in the big kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Cooking}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid927206\charrsid348800 \rquote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
s done in the big kitchen, on the old Cornish range.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Coal fire?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Every Saturday the - this here slab had to be cleaned and - black lead, brasses shining. Well 
my mother wasn't enjoying very good health by the time I left school you see, so - from the time I left school I did it mostly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 When was breakfast eaten in your household?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well the children had their breakfast - about eight to go to school, fath
er would be - coming in after - he did his milking, half past eight - for his breakfast.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 The children's breakfast time, it would be the children and mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What did you usually have to eat and drink at breakfast}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid927206\charrsid348800 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Porridge. Eggs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Do you - remember what you used to have to drink with the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Why - the same as the rest.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Tea or cocoa?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, cocoa sometimes. We were - as a family, great water drinkers. I - for years I never drank anything else and - on
e or two of my brothers never drank anything else but cold water.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You didn't have a well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. That all had to be fetched. But - in the wintertime we used - were using the rainwater.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Plenty of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well in our climate it seems to be doesn't it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you have anything different on Sundays for breakfast?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, we never had anything different for Sundays for breakfast. We always had good food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What time was the midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Twelve. Twelve to half past twelve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you children come home for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, we always stayed at school for - midday meal. Carried our dinners then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You used to carry your dinners?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Carry our dinners then, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Could you have anything warmed at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Not in the schoo
l, there was an old lady that used to clean the school, because a - the teacher was living in the next - place, and take us to school, we used to go in - there and have cocoa - with the teacher, my sister - just - just my sister and I that - that - went. 
A
nd - in those days - there was the firm of Hosken, Trevithick and Polkinghorn at Hayle and they were carrying - flour and - goods to a mill a Trannack, and that passed Chynhale school and quite often - when they were carrying on the road, they would give 
u
s - a ride home. They - they would stop and water their horses down there, they would - give us a ride home, I can remember different - names of these men that used to give us a ride home with sometimes four of us or sometimes two, and other days they wou
l
d be going past our place going from Hayle to Lizard with four houses and wagons carrying - flour, grain and - stuff. They'd be going past our place - in the morning when we - leave - go to school about half past eight so they must - have - they had to le
ave about half past seven from Hayle, and in the evening when we come home from school they'd be coming back from Lizzard and - various places where they'd been with their loads of flours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They would be taking loads of flour?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They wouldn't be bringing corn for grinding?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, they would be taking loads of flour - out. The - when they come back they were empty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They would be going to the farms with the flour?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, they wouldn't carry it to the farms, they would carry it to 
- the stores, see they knew that they didn't supply the farmer. They supplied the mills. And the stores. And then the farmer went to the - mill, he carried his corn down there to be ground, and bring it back. But they were supplying the - mills you see.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Who did Hosken, Trevithick and Polinghorn take the flour to then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well, they took the - flour to the - millers. The people that had the business. See?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 There were a number of milers around then were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, there were different mille
rs around. There. Down to Trevarno - there was the mill, 'cos plenty of water down there, and at Coverack Bridges, there a big - two mills up there. And they would come with their loads of flour and - come back empty. But was it was wasn't it from Hayle t
o
 Lizzard with four horses and a wag - and wagons for men, 'cos they men had to be up - in the morning to groom their horses and get them - feed them before they - start off to work, and in the evening sometimes it maybe five o'clock - when they were going
 back - from Lizzard - and Mullion - there, well time they got down to Hayle with - horses and wagons, then they had to - groom their - horses and feed them before they leave work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Where would they be bringing the flour from? At Hayle?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well come down from Hull - or - or Liverpool I suppose by boat. It came in see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 So the flour that was used was what came from other parts of the country?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Not what was grown here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. No, not what was grown here. In the - spring time they w
ould - delivering seed corn, and that kind of thing, for - that would come - or sometimes come from abroad. Canada and that. There brought to boats in lot of - a lot of - commerce done by the boat - boats, Porthleven and all around, all the ports was used
 in they days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Would there have been anything else besides flour and seed out?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
No, it was - Hosken and Trevithick and Polkinghorn - in they days were - later on they - used to carry - goods to shops, but it - had changed hands then, they went fr
om - Hosken Trevitick - to Nicholson I think then, and then they were - come round to the shops with - groceries, later on, but not when I was going to school. They didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They didn't actually come to your farm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, they didn't come to our farm because - they - they were -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Your father knew them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes, knew them by different names. There was a Mr Phil Hosken, there was Mr Stee Hosken, there was Mr Dasw, we knew all these names, because we knew the ones that would give us a ride, there w
as one man - he would never - give us a ride. And there was one - now if you're going to ride, he said, you've to sing some hymns, no old silly nonsense.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 So you used to sing hymns on the way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, we used to - sing hymns on the way back. And som
etimes - in the summertime - one or two would bring their wives up with them - so far as our place to go blackberrying picking. Days outing that was. And then ride back when they come back - by night time, yes, that was - they used to like that, then come
 
in our place to have tea. That was - quite - quite a picnic yes. Well then - at that time Wheal Vor Mine was working. And that was only two fields away - from our place. And when my sister and I went to bed, if we slept in the middle room, and with the wi
n
dow wide open - you could see when they opened a big door out to the mine and stoking up the fire. You could see it - oh, quite a flame - quite as plain as anything, you could see anybody - silhouetted across there. That was Wheal Vor. And the traction en
gines was - carrying coal from Hayle then to Wheal Vor Mine, and the roads was - in wintertime when there was rain, were just like a mud mire, black.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Not made up, stone roads?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. Yes, stone roads then, yes. Our fruit trees in the summertime would be clouded with dust from - from the roads. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What time would you have your evening meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
In the summertime we would have had evening meal when the children come home from school. But in the wintertime - we would wait until father finished 
the - milking and - about six o'clock or - half past six then. He always liked to finish off his - evening work before - have tea.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Would your tea be the main meal of the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 We wouldn't - we children would have something hot when we come home 
from school but it wouldn't be the main meal not for father. He - he would have his - in - cooked meal - meal the midday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Do you remember what you used to have to eat for your midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. No, when - when - when we come home. All sorts of th
ings. We had - plenty of meat and - and pork in those days. Because we used to - kill a pig - ourselves and salt that in, there was always plenty of meat going. So -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Salt, what would it be in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Sometimes - well the hams you would rub dry salt and hang them up, and - the - the other -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 In the diary?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
In the dairy, yes, or in - no, not in the dairy because - you'd hang - sometimes hang the ham in the fringle - there, to - smoke it up a bit and - it was drier there see, you hang they in the 
kitchen were the heat was so - until they's dried off, and - yes, smoke them, but - if - some perhaps you put in - pickle, some - yes, that would be in the butter, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Pickle them with salt?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Salt, yes. Salt and - well make a brine, salt and sug
ar you know, yes, make a brine there and - and that's how - and we always had plenty of meat. Because meat was - real - really cheap. I remember going into the butchers cart with my mother and - the butcher saying, this is - when the war - had started, fi
r
st war had started, butcher saying, well missus, when beef do get to a shilling a pound, John Trerice is not coming around. And he didn't come around after - he said, a shilling a pound is enough for any - meat. So he never came around after meat got a sh
i
lling a pound, he finished, because he was getting quite elderly and he - he wasn't coming round to people. And a lot of times I've seen my mother give - the pork butcher - a shilling, say, here put in a shillingsworth to old Liza up there, there's a - so
me old lady she knew up there, well you had a nice bit of - pork or meat for a shilling then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Would you have anything different for either of your meals on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Generally had - roast beef or chicken, if - if we had chicken on the farm we had chicken, but - generally roast beef - for Sundays, yes.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Anything special for tea on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
No, we'd - we - always had plenty of cream. And we always had - always made jam, and always had - we had plenty of cream and jam. And it was quite a tr
eat to have tinned fruit. That was nearly out of the question but occasionally it would be tinned fruit - or prunes, I mean that was - that was quite a treat. And a tir- trifle, that was - really it. But - because we had cream and jam and tarts and that -
 we - never used to have much different - Sundays, not than any other day.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You could have that every other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 We could have that every day, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did mother or father make their own bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, always. Always made bread. Bread, cake -
 seed - cake. Splits. You was considered to be lazy if you bought bread. Well it - bread never came around to buy it, if you went to the - bakers shop you might - buy it, but bread was never brought around in they days. We used to have flour by the bale. 
A bale of white flour. Always had that in mill.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Which mill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
They went to Trevenner mill and - father used to grow - a little wheat, and then we would carry the - wheat down, have it ground, and bring home the - what they call the seconds for brown flour. We always had that - kept -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Mother made bread with that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, brown, yes. The wholemeal, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did mother ever bottle any fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well they weren't - heard tell of bottling fruit, that came when I got - older. She
 always made - jam. Always pickled. Done pickles. Pickled onions. And we always - patted butter. I used to - and when I got older I - I was home working with my father, I used to have a lot of - pots brought in the summertime. Even from down Scilly Isles.
 People brought pots - for to have - butter potted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And you would sell it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes. Yes, they'd bring their pots, yes, and have butter - potted, yes, and some Hayle, Helston - around, because that used to be the thing. So - and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And it was plentiful?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. And well it was cheap then, yes. Yes. And we used to pickle.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you pickle eggs and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, we pickled eggs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 For family use?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. That's all. For cooking too. You couldn't - well they weren't very nice I don't think to boil, but - for - cooking mostly, }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid927206\charrsid348800 omelettes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800  and things like that you could - use them in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did mother make any wine or medicines for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I think she used to make some sloe wine one time. There. I can remember her doing - salting
 in pilchards. I never liked them, they'd always too salt and - I - I rather have a potato with no pilchard on it, these salt pilchards. And we used to - have pudden skins, if you - if you know what that is - because - we were killing - perhaps two or thr
e
e pigs - in - Mondays and two or three again the end of the week when we had pigs to kill, and we always stripped the bellies - washed - out the pots and made pudden skins and always - cleaned the bellies and took off the fat and run down the - fat and al
w
ays had pans of lard, or bussas of lard there all the time. We never bought any lard hardly. And when the war was - on - on - on - we cleaned all the entrails from the - pig, that went away as sausage meat, all the small parts and everything, you washed t
hem all out and - that went away as - to make sausage}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid927206\charrsid348800 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 meat they said.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What did you clean them with, soap?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
No, water. Wat - water, yes. We had to wash them and wash them, some - people would - if they had a river nearby we used to go down to the r
iver, and wash them in the river, but we never had the - running stream, we used to put them under the tank and turn the tap and - wash them with rainwater.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was any beer brewed for the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Used to make - buy hops, and make some - hops - herb
y beer. And some people used to come up our place and pick - black elder to make - steep - dried elder and steep it, the elder, for a drink in winter time. I made - used to make some wine when I got older, blackberry wine and - rhubarb wine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 But not when you were at home with your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. No. Not when my mother - no. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did your father or mother grow their own vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Never bought any - vegetables. And we had some apple trees and always had a lot of small fruit,
 blackcurrants and gooseberries and - made preserves, jam and - I don't think we wasted anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did they ever buy any tinned or dried vegetables or fruit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Oh we never heard tell of dried vegetables then. Used to buy some dried fruit at times. 
Apricots. Apple rings. They used to be quite plentiful. When - your own apples got done you could buy dried apple rings, yes, we used to like them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You kept livestock of course, hens?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Pigs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Pigs.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you have any goats?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, never had any goats.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Who looked after the livestock?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well - father done - did that, yes. Yes. Did a little milking and - fed a few fat bullocks in the wintertime. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What about the hens, did father look after then as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, mo - mother, when she was able to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you ever have tinned meat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
I don't remember my mother buying - any tinned meat. Used to have - tinned salmon sometimes. But I don't remember her buying any tinned meat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you ever have rabbit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes. Used to have rabbit. Especially - corn harvest time when you caught the rabbits in the cornfield, had - cutting corn used to - have rabbit. We were never very fond of rabbit, we used to like - if it was a young rabbit. Take out all the bone and make 
rabbit pasty.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Would you get the rabbits from your own fields?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes, from the - cornfields, you know, when the binder was working. That used to be quite a - treat to be out with the binder, chasing the rabbits.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were you allowed to talk during meals or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well - if you had something to say you could say it. But it was the adults that take - took up most of the time talking, especially - if anybody else come in. We used to have a pork butcher used to come around - Wednesdays, and he alw
ays had dinner at our place. And the conversation Wednesdays would be - about the sermon on Sundays. Unless something turned up about the choir or - that, but that used to be - the conversation - Wednesdays, was the - preacher on Sundays. What did you thi
nk of him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Could you choose what you wanted to eat from what was cooked or did you have to eat a bit of everything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I don't think we - were a bit fussy that way at all, what was there we - put before us we ate. Some}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid927206\charrsid348800  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 things you like better than ot
hers, we never had any - trouble I don't think in eating, well we had cream and jam and things we liked. Sometimes it would be airy cake. But we weren't a lot, not for heavy cakes and - sometimes it would be potato cake, we made a potato cake and - beef o
n the top of it. We liked what was put before us, I don't think we ever had any picky -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What would your parents attitude be if you left food uneaten on the plate?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well unless you were sick, you had to eat up your meal. There was something wrong i
f you weren't eating your meal properly, because it was always good food.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Could you ask for a second helping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, we always had plenty, in - in our place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 If there was something on the table you wanted like the salt could you ask someone t
o pass it to you or did you have to wait until it was offered to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I think we took it most times.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were you allowed to bring toys or a book to the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, we never read - at meals. And - toys, we didn't have much toys then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were you expected to hold your knife and fork in a certain way and sit in a certain way?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, we were always taught to - use the knife and fork properly and sit up. I used to be told a lot of times about stooping forward.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 When could you leave the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
You always asked to be excused. To leave the table. We always had grace on Sundays and quite often when - at evening meal, we always had grace - there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Who said grace?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Father quite often, and then - when the children - when we children got older we took it in turns to - say it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did all the family sit at the table for the meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you usually sit in your own place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. All sat - had a - sat in the same place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How was the meal served, who by?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 When mother was able she was - serve the - but afterwards I was the one that - took over and - it came to my lot quite often.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was there any special order for serving?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 When they came in and was all sitting down - the - meal was served up and - they all started to eat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Just go round the table?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Just - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No special order?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Where did the younger brothers and sister sit before they could feed themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They sat in their highchair.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Who would feed them?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Mot
her or me. It didn't seem very long before they fed theirselves. It doesn't seem very long when you're a good many - don't take long, today I think just one - the ones that are fussed over a lot, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did one help the other sometimes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was mother an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes I think she was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 If you had worries could you share them with her or not?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well if you had anything - she'd always listen - to you, if you had anything, but I don't remember having - much 
- not what you call much worries. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did mother show affection?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was father an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Oh I suppose he was easy - easy to talk to, but - he seemed to be - you always went to mother first I think. If there's a
nything about outside - you could -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Go to father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes, you could talk to him - about anything but - it was mother - well we came home with our stories, they would always listen to what - we had to say or anything turned up - at school or anythin
g like that, they'd always - we used to bring the news - home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did father show affection very much?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well I don't suppose he was very demonstrative, not - no. But he depended on - when he got older depended on - the family to - help, you know, yes, and look after him, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How did your parents expect you to behave towards them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I think they took it for granted that we'd do what we're told.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did they ever say that you should hit back or not if another child hurt you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I don't -
 coming home from school one day - there was a family - that used to drive - a donkey jingle to school. Twelve children they were. And one day the oldest brother didn't come and I said - I'll drive you home. And I had no more idea about driving the donkey
 
that I did about an aeroplane. Got on very well 'til we come down to a cross roads and I had to turn to go down - the road where they lived and I was a bit too near - the hedge, and I drove them up over the stone, over goes the jingle, out goes the childr
en, and my father came on - at that time - breaking in a colt. And I had - some row. Why did you take it in your head to drive that donkey, I don't - I know I had a fuss, I - I would do things be - fore I thought you know I think. Bit forthright.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Volunteer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes. Yes, forthright like see, it was before I thought anything about it, I was - I know I had a fussing for that. And another time I told the girls bicycle, and fell off, well I had a fussing for that. I put my thumb out., you see, and was put
 it in there, when I come home I couldn't move it, they said - they said I have to go to the doctor and so father - go to the doctor, he said, let me see, and he come and he pulled it out. Well it never been right. See? It was put out, but never been righ
t, you didn't go to the doctor for every - little thing, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You could drive a pony?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Drive a horse, yes, yes, drive a - we had to go mill when the war was on a lot, didn't matter driving - then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you'd grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I expect they thought they'd grow up to be quite sensible, seeing - seeing they came from sensible people, there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did your parents bring you up to consider certain things important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 There was one thing my
 mother used to say - we used to - have our groceries - over in a little shop - at Nancegollan, where there was a widow woman, she kept this little shop, and she was - a member of the chapel, and we're - she used to say now we must always help out they ki
n
d of people, you see. Go Mrs Woods for your things because - she's - on her own, she got to get her living, used to tell - and - she was always - sending little bits of things - over - to anybody, you know, if there's anybody sick or anything like that, w
e always had to carry - a little bit of anything. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Consider other people?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes. Then we used to go - sometimes down to grandma's to - help - do little things on Saturdays. Now don't you go taking anything from grandma mind. Well she'd always 
make us take a shilling you see, but we was never - now don't you tell your mother that I gave you a shilling. Then my mother would - go off - out to stay up with anybody that's sick, you know, by night, they used to. When she really - she wasn't able to 
do it. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 That would be neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes. Yes. I know one time she was - went a mile there. Might be more from Nancegollan up to Releath to stay up - a man who had - that had pneumonia. Well she had a family herself - really, and she wasn't in go
od health. She was - taken with - whooping cough and it turned to - consumption. Tore her chest see, and - when I was about nineteen or twenty she wasn't well and when I was twenty-one she died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did your parents bring you up to behave towards your brothers and sister in certain ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well I think they always got on very well, maybe a little - quarrels like children do, but we always - got on - very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What would they think about swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 We never heard it. Never heard nothing - nothing like that. In they days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 If grown ups were talking were you allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 If your parents - if you did something that your parents disapproved if what would happen? For example the overturned donkey?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Oh well, we - had a good row. How did you know any better - what - why did you think to do it? You know, that - you had a good talking to.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Usually a good talking to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, usually a good talking to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Would that be from your father or mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Both of them would have a go, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Do you remember any other punishment, put to bed or anything like that?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Would you say that you received the ideas you had about how to behave from both your parents or would one play a more important part 
than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well that was the order of the - household I think, mean, I don't think very much difference in between - mother and father for that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Both the same?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 When you had a birthday would that be different from any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I don't remember having anything different on me birthday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Can you remember anything you did with your mother or father together on Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well, I - I - Christmas when we were - were small - we kept up Christmas but we never ha
d a Christmas tree. No, I don't remember ever having a Christmas tree but - was always preparations for Christmas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What sort of preparations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well, you know, the - cake and mince meat and all that kind of thing. Food - food was made. And - we us
ed to have this old lady from Nancegollan - the - Mrs Ward. She always came to our house for Christmas Day. And we always - remembered - other people, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 She was alone was she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, she was alone and - we - another old lady used to live o
ut - in two fields, always had to carry out saffron bun to her. I don't know how old she was then but she lived to be ninety-nine. There.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you have any music or sing-songs or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Oh yes, we had - we had organ at - at home see. Oh we had
 a lot of - music, around the organ, yes, we always had - Christmas - well on any time, in the wintertime if the weather's so bad and father didn't - wasn't able to go to chapel we always had - plenty of music 'cos - if we had fire down the front room - t
h
e organ was going - pretty well best part of the night, yes. And Christmas carols and we used to go out with - child - other children singing Christmas carols, round the village - there. But we were - more than a mile and a half away you see. And to go by
 
yourself, it was - a long way for - I don't think we went very often not a - alone. We used to - father used to go with us sometimes, take us over. And then we used to meet - these here - great timber wagons coming from Camborne, pulling - with four horse
s
, in the dark. No lights, they carried not lights on these great long timber wagons, have you ever seen them? Or heard of them? Yes. And - timber for - for the mines, yes. From Wheal Vor - and - they used to be carriers over there, and they used to go eve
ry day to - to the mines with these great - four horse}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid927206\charrsid348800 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
 timber things. Oh great - things that would stretch out yards behind - the length - yes, the - the length of them, and all they had was the candle - light, and the man - that was driving these horses quite often'd stop down \{BLANK\}
 and been in a pub and he would shouting and bawling but - leaving it to the horse - the old horses with the - and the roads was narrow, and if we come out and meet they in the dark we had to - go in in the hedge and wait 'til
 they's gone on 'cos you could hear them - coming and on a frosty night for ages, miles away, there. So we never used to like to - be going out - by ourselves.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They had a candle in a lantern did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes. Well just a little glow - lamp, it was the horses that took the old man home. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did anyone else besides your father play the organ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well when I got old enough I did. Yes. Lots of hours I spent - holding the - youngest - my youngest brother, when he was a baby about seven or eight months old, my lap, playing him off to sleep, lots of times. But - better be doing that than working.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was there anyone in the family who sang?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. I did. Yes. And my father had a very good voice. I had - I had a voice. To be trained reall
y, but - money weren't plentiful enough. No time - or - I mean that - I think they thought and getting on see they had to buy this place and there was a mortgage on it, getting on and paying off - the mortgage, there was no - money for anything - extra, w
hereas - today - well for my children I wanted for them to have - so much education as they could have and have the best that was going, but there was no time or money - for anything extra - in they days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You would make music together of a winter evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did your parents play any games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes. Yes. Yes. Games. Snap was the - one of the big games and - father liked playing - draughts. Sit down and play - play draughts he would. But mother didn't have much time - to
 - join in much because time she - done her work well there's always mending to do. Grandma used to help to do the mending but there was always sewing and mending and knitting to do for - family, there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you do any sewing or knitting to help out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes. We helped out. Knit stockings. Yes. And at school I - was about the only one that could - do a heel properly and U had to go around - class telling the others which way to do a heel.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were there books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Can you remember any that you had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well I can remember different prizes that we had. I think - a lot of books for our prizes, our - parents would pick so as they could read the stories themselves. But I know - one book that I had, it was a great big bo
ok, it was - Three Boys in the World West Land. Wild North Land. Well, it was - stories about the Wild West and how they used to live and that, and I can remember my father reading these stories to us, and remember crying - to - think what these little ch
ildren had to suffer and that - and that, I know, that - remember that one. And Anya Swan's book, and Joseph Hawkins books. Silas Hawkins books, they used to have that one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Religious?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well, no, they - well they were reli - I suppose but they were - also - wholesome stories, good - good old yarns then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 He was the Reverend Silas Hawkins?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes. Yes, well they were good yarns. But - they weren't books really until we got older that we could read. But I think the parents - had them to read them themselves and save them up for the children.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What about newspapers, did you take any newspapers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes, we used to have the - newspaper. When the war was on we had to go every day over to Nancegollan station for the paper, and that - we didn't
 mind that really, that was of a outing. Because - there was two or three porters over the station see so we could go in there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You were in your teens by this time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. About fourteen to fifteen then. Well I hadn't left school, not when the - 
first war started. And I can remember my mother and father coming home from - Helston, and saying - my dear life, mother said, they women in Helston today, they were in some way. Because the war have started and their boys is going - to the war, and they'
s
 in there crying. Well, she said, that won't last very long, they'll be home again very soon. Well I didn't you see, it went on for years and by the time - I went to - it wasn't long, about twelve months afterwards I went out to a - Constantine to stay wi
t
h my aunty - and my mother writing me, saying, now be careful, don't you go down in they woods by that river, because you never know where they Germans are going to turn up with their bombs. But - it went on - well while that I was in my teens and - when 
-
 had to do a lot outdoors then, in - corn, I've been up on the ricks pitching corn until you couldn't - hardly see the sheaf coming up and - find your way down on the - twenty stave ladder there. And I had to go mill and do all sorts of thing when - by th
at time, 'cos labour scarce, you couldn't have nobody to help see there but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You used to go to the mill with the corn?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Horse and cart, carrying the corn and go down for it, yes. And - that - when the war was on we - we make - was making butter -
 but we weren't - putting of it in pounds, we'd just wash it and not salt it, wash it in grains and put it in muslin hampers - a muslin, put in hampers and carry it to the station, and - sent it off by train - to Morcambelake, because the price was a bit 
b
etter up there. So we had - Morcambelake yes, there was a big butter factory there, and the price was a bit better and - we were - we were doing that one time I know. Because - before the war - butter - the - buyers was only giving eightpence a pound. The
n.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you have any magazines in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Christian Herald. Never saw comics. I - I don't - never - I don't know whether they was printed, Punch and Judy I suppose but not - or Punch was that, but - not - no so such things as comics, I don't remember ever seeing anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Do you ever remember your mother or father reading aloud to you or to each other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well when we came home from school, we had to - recite - what we learnt. Not what they learnt. Remember standing up against
 the glass cupboard, and - telling about the burial of Sir John Moore. We had to say how clever we was I suppose.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Do you remember a funeral in the family in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I don't - remember - not a funeral - in our family, I remember father and mo
ther going away - to a funeral. But I don't remember - a funeral in our family. But when I was fifteen I was a bearer to a funeral. To a girl that died. And that was - quite an entertainment. For us. We had - a - fashionable that year for to have - long -
 white voile dresses with em - embroidery that length, you know, from down here, and most of the girls in Nancegollan had all these here embroidered dresses, and we went to this funeral, was - six girls picked out to go to this funeral.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 White dresses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
White dresses and black sashes around here. And really - it was - it was nice. Was walking then, had to walk and that was - about half mile down the road I suppose. This - and she was - she was seventeen, eighteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You walked in procession from the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
From the - to the - yes, to the church. And it was a Miss Kirkeek, she was a lay preacher, rather masculine looking woman, but she took a lot of these funerals, and she dressed something like a man. And she took a lot of these - funerals. 
In they days. And she came from Nancegollan and they had her to - have this funeral. And we were singing all the way up the road, but before we started, the undertaken gave we girls a shilling each. See? Well - I never had nowhere to put the shilling but 
here in the palm of me hand under me go}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid927206\charrsid348800  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
love. And going up along, this old shilling got in under the pole. Another girl and I was big girls we was in the front, and I put me hand up to shake it out - you know, move this old shilling, it rolled out. And the 
girl's father jumped out - he was chief mourner, and jumped out - picked up this shilling and called the undertaker, one of the girls have lost a shilling, he said. Well we was singing all the way up the road, we changed with some boys or some men there, 
b
ut we - we had to leave the house - with that, and we had to carry it in chapel. We was bearers from the house. But it was quite an entertainment, that - to we - to we - girls. This girl - died there, of course she was in consumption. We were the chosen b
earers. And we - we - father said the girls are looking very nice, it didn't seem to be much grief you know there, he said, the girls are looking lovely, and then we all had to go back to tea. But it was all walking funerals in they days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And singing all the way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, singing all the way, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Who attended as mourners do you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well, the father and the mother. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were they a big family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And - yes, were quite - a - relatives, there was another - two other sisters and a brother - there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did they wear mourning clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Oh yes, they were in deep black. They were. Everybody wore mourning clothes, didn't they. In they days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 If they couldn't buy clothes they had black armbands?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were you ever taken visiting neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
We had - as - one - my sister and I used to go down to - grandma's when she was living at Trenwheal and then we had to go and see different people, different old people - that my mother used to know, you see carrying 
a little bit of something to them, or perhaps they had apples and we'd have a few apples to bring home. And one old - lady was in - there was two sisters living together, and one was in the bed all the time, she never - never used to get out and we used t
o
 have to go in to see her and she'd have the sheet up like that and she - always shook hands with us and the room - the bedroom window was never - never opened, it was always stuffy, and before we came home we'd always have some apples given us. And these
 apples had been kept in a drawer with camphor balls. But in the end these two old souls was moved into the Union - and - well -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Where was the Union?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Helston, yes. And do you know they found a lot of money - around - there - did - gold sovereigns
 then - around in different places, and they had a - lot of books, the Commen - Clark's Commentary on the Bible, and my father had to have them. That was the - will that - that he had to have them, but after she got in to Helston the - she was out the bed
 and - you know, lived quite a while after that. The one that had - was in the bed all along, but we always had to go in to see here and carrying something to see her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And her sister tended her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes. But they never had the windows opened you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 She would put the bed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid927206\charrsid348800 -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 sheet up over her mouth?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 That was to keep from having your germs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, yes, I suppose so, I suppose - she just put her hand - we always had to shake hands. We weren't very old. No. And we always went 
to - down at that place to tea treat. For - where my mother came from, down Trenwheal tea treats. Yes, we always had to go down there. For anything was doing down to Trenwehal chapel - we always went. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They had a small chapel there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, a small chapel. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Mother would take you to these?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes, mother, yes. Or sometimes when we got a bit bigger - we would be sent off down the road - by ourselves and - mother and father do up the work and come down afterwards.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you go out visiting any other relations but your granny?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well - I didn't have many - relations around because - we - some lived at Nancegollan and we went there but - for - away I don't think we had any - more of them that lived away any distance anywhere.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And these were your mother's old friends that you used to visit?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, mother - yes, our mother's old friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were you taken shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 When we wanted new clothes we went shopping. And when we got old enough we went to - were sent to}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid927206\charrsid348800  shop at Nancegollan for grocer}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 ies and anything that's - wanted.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Who took you shopping for your clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Mother. Mother. Yes, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Never father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well, no, he - he would drive us sometimes - drive us sometimes with the horse and trap but - he
 wasn't interested not to - you could have what you wanted but - he wouldn't - not be interested going in the shops nor nothing like that, he would be doing perhaps something on his own. Want something. Didn't seem to be - a lot of time - spent about clot
hes - then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Do you remember any other outings with your parents, like Bank Holidays or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Once a year - we - when the school - when we had our school holidays, father would either - put the horse in the wagon and we went down to 
Praa Sands - whole family, grandma go too. And perhaps one or two neighbours - besides, you know, make a party perhaps. Or - we had - he have - put the horse and trap, and gone down to Carbis Bay. One outing, we - couldn't have the two. But - we used to g
o - when we got older, my sister and I, the Band of Hope, we went on those outings to the Jersey Cars and - that, that was - quite a highlight then.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Where did they go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Went to - used to go to - Carbis - sometimes - St. Ives. Then when we got dow
n to Lelant, we all had get out the Jersey Car to walk up the hill to help ease the horses. There. I think once or twice they went to - Perranporth. But I - we never went on that - journey. Ours used to be - Carbis Bay. And that would - that was - that wa
s nice that was. You would carry all your food, great basket. Sun would be roast - have a great roast chicken and - well - stacks of food they used to carry, great - basket come up there. And whose - who - could get up on top of the Jersey Car to -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Open top?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, open top. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 There used to be a tearooms in Carbis Bay didn't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes, Pains Tea Rooms then. You could have tea or - take your food and have - the - drinks see. And then walk from - Carbis Bay into St Ives and back again, or else go in on the train. Quite often walk in and back again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you ever go away for a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
I don't suppose my mother and father ever had - a holiday. When we got older - well mind used to be a working holiday, when I got - fifteen, four
teen or fifteen, because I could make butter, and - go out to Constantine with me aunt was milking a dairy for - make her butter for she to go away - for a few days. And - we had sis - aunts living in Penzance, we used to go down there. We used to go down
 
there once - father always drove down there once a year to see a sisters and - yes, for the day. And - horse and trap. And our horse - would never drink the water down Penzance, he'd go all day, she would never drink. And - she would go very slow going do
wn and coming home - you couldn't stop her, she'd - come like a mail-cart coming home you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did any other members of the family go to stay with your aunt like you did, at Constatine?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, not to - well my brother went out there once with us, h
e too was working then when he got old enough to help in the harvest, he - he - that's what they had us for then. But we used to have cousins come to stay from Bodmin, there. And aunty and that, but - and cousin - aunties used to come up from Penzance. Bu
t -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You didn't go there to stay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes, I used to go Penzance when I got - oh - fourteen or fifteen I went to Penzance at different times. Went there the once though to have all my teeth out, because my teeth was decayed - when I was very young and I had all my top - top teeth out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You'd go by train then would you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, there was a bus running. Then,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 A horse bus?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, a motor bus from - Nancegollan to Penzance. No, you couldn't go by train - then, because that was more expensive
, you could walk to Breage and catch a - a bus, my mother would walk to Breage, and catch - caught a bus to go to Pensance. To go to - Penzance by train - well that was - dearer you see so -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was there any difference, how did you spend your Saturdays while you were a school girl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Playing. Quite often. Go over to a friend's to play. Or - that - friend would come over to our place. I remember once being sent to Nancegollan - with - my sister and I with this milk strainer to be mended over to the - b
lacksmith's shop. And we went down - to the blacksmith's shops place and they had a beautiful gay house these children did down there, handsome things in their - gay house. And we stayed over there so long - nearly all the day, that in the evening - we wa
s coming home and we brought the strainer and met father coming, wild he was, we're waiting for the strainer and - we was off in Nancegollan playing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was this a little play house they had?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, yes, you - what you -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Doll's house like?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
No. They had own - own little playhouse out in the field, they made it, and they used to call them gays. And they had lovely things in their - gay house, we never had no things like that, they had - lovely broken teapots and all you know. Lovely things.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Broken?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They were all broken pieces but - theirs were heaps better than ours. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 We used to call them sherds and gays. Broken bits of bone china?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes. Yes. All sorts of things, but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You'd imagine they were all -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes. Well you made your own entertainment then you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you have any punishment for that then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
We had a lot of fussing because he was home waiting for this - it was evening time then. A lot of fussing - waiting for this strainer and - we was over there playing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you wear different clothes on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Always had best clothes for Sundays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were you allowed to play games on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I don't think it ever entered head, well we didn't have any time. The - morning afternoon and evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Your parents though would think it wrong to work or play on a Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Never did - anything - that wasn't necessary. Cut up Saturdays - for Sundays. Sundays was the day of rest but it was the busiest day of the week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 The place you went to on Sundays, what denomination was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well it was Wesleyan then. Wesleyan. And - oh a lot - a lot - a lot of people came then, in they days. Everybody around would - everybody around went to - chapel then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were there any Sunday school outings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
No, had tea treat. We had tea treat held - held - and held at Nancegollan. And used to march down - along to Trevarno Grounds, behind the band and back again. And a sweltering hot day - walking all that way for nothing. No one has 
to have a drink or anything. No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 After you did that what would happen then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Oh then come back and - have your buns, and tea. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 At the Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 At the - in the field. And - play games - then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were there any other social activities organized by the chapel that you took part in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
The Band of Hope. Was the Band of Hope was the great thing in those days. Used to get up entertainments. Little sketches and dialogues and things, they made their own entertainment then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes. East - at Easter-time - father always got a cantata or something up - in the choir, that - Good Friday was always a - Easter was always busy - time at the chapel.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You were in the choir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Any other activities apart from the cantata that you can think of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Oh well - special occasions, Harvest Festival, always got up anthems and - carol service Christmas and that - that kind of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How often did you have to have choir practice?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Every Friday it was choir practice. Tuesdays was preaching service.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Who took that then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well the minister would come - then, and Thursdays father had a class - he was class leader, he had a class - meeting, and I used to - when I was twelve - I used to go with him. A
nd it wasn't a place for children, really. These old people used to come and they would say the same things and start to cry and - the same things they would say every time and another girl said to me once, we haven't got to be like that have we?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Can you remember anything else about the prayer meetings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
The funny thing was - we had a dog that would follow us everywhere, and this dog followed us to prayer meeting, and he got inside the Sunday school door - and dear brother started to pray, and th
e dog started to howl, before he'd finished - we didn't know who was praying, the dog or the - brother. And then one dear old lady went down in the chapel to put her hymn book in the seat, and she got locked in, everybody else went out - and went home and
 
locked the door, and she was locked inside. And she got in quite a stew, she started shouting, broke the glass - of the window with her umbrella, then in time her son-in-law - had missed her from time and thought it was time for her to return, he come up 
and he found her in the chapel. So he - opened the door from - inside - there with another key and - took her home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were you taught to say prayers at night at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, we always said our prayers before we went to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you ever have family prayers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
The time that we had family prayers would be of a Sunday night if the weather was too bad and my father couldn't - go to chapel, he would - read - a portion - from the Bible, or perhaps read us a story out of the book and have - some sin
ging around the organ. The organ was generally in use - when father was - there for a evening or - or had any spare time, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did father take any interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well I don't think they - took a lot of interest though - when there was ele
ction time - used to have some strong arguments sometimes with people come around. He was - Liberal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did he ever go to political meetings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I can remember him going to Truro. Several of them from round about that was like minded and - at the time
 when Hay Morgan was running - they went to Truro. And we had a minister at Wall, Reverend Crossley Holt who used to get quite - warm, quite heated up - politics in those days, and they all went to Truro. There was quite a rowdy meeting - I remember them 
saying. Sir Edwin Dyran - Lawrence was - the opposition - side. And the - opposition - opposition side upset the platform and - but they came home all safe and sound again. And - Hay Morgan got in at that time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Why do you think he held those views? A Liberal view?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well those days there was only the - Liberal and the Conservative party, and I think he - he thought the Liberal party was the - working man's - government.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was mother interested in politics at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I think she used - when it
 came voting - she was eligible to vote - voted Liberal the same as father used to vote, but I think she was - what you might say very interested.-
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You remember them voting in an election before 1919?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Went down to Godolphin Cross, yes, they used to vote Godolphin Cross. Put the horse in the trap to drive down there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
In some places at that time some men felt risked losing their jobs or their house if they voted different from their employers, do you think the people felt that at all around your way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes. I do. Because I remember going to school - the Bickford-Smiths at Trevarno were - very - Liberal minded people and vote - were Liberal, but they changed on - Home - Home Rule was it? I think. Turned Conservative. And at the time whe
n Hay Morgan was running - I remember the gardener coming in to tell the children and the teachers at school that Hay Morgan got in. And a boy went home to our father of it - they - all they people down Trevarno didn't vote for Hay Morgan, they voted Cons
e
rvative for Sir Edwin Duran-Lawrence this time, so my father said, yes, well they voted because they had to vote - the same as - the Bickford-Smith family, but, he said, the man that came in to tell you - that Hay Morgan had got in, he voted for Hay Morga
n. He didn't change his views because - the Bickford-smith's voted - changed theirs. But they did in those days, they do anything the Squire - the -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Bickford-Smith was the Squire?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was - they were the squire round there, they owned the farms around - then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you ever come across them in your life in the village? Did they take any active part in the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well at that time when we were going to - Chynhale day school - old Mrs Bickford-Smith was on Bard of Governors, she was a regular
 visitor to the school, and they built - Chynhale - chapel, they were great Methodists in those days. Took - a very active part - in the school and Sunday school - then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did your parents take any political activity apart from election time and voting?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. They didn't have the time to do it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Apart from chapel was father able to take part in anything else in any spare time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, the - chapel activities took up - all the spare time. Choir practice. Prayer meeting. Trustee of the - chapel,
 any - repairs or anything want doing -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was he interested in the band at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes. Always went to Bugle Band Contests. Very fond of - band music, or any kind of music. At one time they had a little band at - Nancegollan, I don't think he was act
ually in it. And they used to practice - in an old cottage - nearby. And one mischievous - fellow one night got up on - while they were practicing, got up on the roof of the cottage, by the chimney and - stuffed up the chimney that he smoked the - players
 right out. Used - he used to go to the Royal Cornwall Show.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Where was that held?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well that used to be held in different places, sometimes - Camborne, Falmouth - Helston, Truro, Penzance. They would catch the train quite often.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They would both go to that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, my mother - my mother wouldn't because she'd stay home with the children. But - go Nancegollan station and catch the train.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did mother ever go out to enjoy herself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I can remember her - going to a concert - and taking us
 over to Nancegollan - to a band of Hope of concert. But thinking along that I don't think she went very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was father interested in any sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I don't remember a lot of sport around in those days, not in our - locality. I suppose there woul
d be in the towns - a bit more but - there wasn't much - sport in the - village - then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Never had any pony races or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Used to have donkey races sometimes. I don't remember pony races but - there's much more fun to have - a - donkey races, and see them.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Who would take part in the donkey races?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
There was a family called Hampton, from over to - Townsend and - Gwinear, they had some lovely donkeys, and they used to - take - these donkeys to races. And caused a lot of fun
. Sometimes the donkey would go, sometimes it wouldn't, but - used to cause a lot of fun.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Where would the races be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well they used to have them around - sometimes to the village places, the donkey race. And - at - place - Wendron - used to have 
- what they call Ram Buck Fair. And that was a - very - lively place 'cos it was near the pub and afterwards - there was plenty of drinking and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 That was once a year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 That was once a year there but - the - in the summertime, the - Hamptons woul
d bring their donkeys to perhaps to a tea treat to have a race you know, to - for amusement really. Carleen tea treat, was - used to be a great tea treat in those days, had two bands. And crowds would could come from all over the place to Carleen tea trea
t, and that was the last tea treat of the year. And we always used to go, that was - quite an entertainment, always used to go Carleen tea treat to hear the band - bands - there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was there any special time for tea treats normally?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Carleen tea tre
at is the first Saturday in August. Nancegollan tea treat would be the last Saturday in July. And we use to say that - after Carleen tea treat the days - dropped a hour quickly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did they ever have donkey races with the mining men?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well I can't remember them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They used to ride with donkey and chaise didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes, used to ride a donkey and chaise. Some - miners used to - walk through our - field behind our house. Every Monday morning from Ashdown. Going to the mines at Camborne - the
re. And they'd walk from Ashdown to Lady Gwendoline mine. Come home Saturday afternoons, we'd see - they - coming back again - there. They would lodge in the meantime, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was father a member of any club?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 He took out a Prudential insurance, I don't think he was ever a member of any clubs around then. Not that I can remember.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 When you were a child at home who did you play with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 My sister - and I used to - be playing - play houses out in the mow-hay. In the wet weather we were up in the barn.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did your brothers play with you at all, the little one?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, the brother's - generally in the way. Always doing things you didn't want to do.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were you allowed to get dirty when you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well we always got dirty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were you allowed to play with anyone you pleased or did your parents discourage you from playing with any children?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
No, we could play with anyone - we liked to play with, but there was no one around our place, nearby for us, we had to go a mile and a half -
 away. There was a friend used to come one Saturday - and we used to go her place sometimes. But that was two miles away but - when her auntie and uncle would come over for the evenings sometimes - play then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was there any one of your brothers or your sister that you felt particularly close to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
No, I think we were - all the - the same, I don't remember - well we used to have arguments and all but - I don't remember falling out - with any of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you have any hobbies while you were a schoolchild?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
What did we used to do? Well we had - we left home in the morning you see about half past eight to go to school, by the time we got - back in the evening it was half past four. We were learnt to do certain things at school, we used to bring
 home our sewing and - knitting, used to learn to knit stockings then when I was going to school and I used to be the only one in the school that could - do a French heel properly and I would go around telling - learning the others how to do French heels.
 
But it was always - we always had knitting on the loom - needles, as soon as we learnt to knit - we were - knitting stockings for father, knitting stockings for ourself. Grandma - would knit too. And the wool would be quite hard in they days. Not nice and
 
soft like it is today. And I used to - was always fond of playing the - organ too. A lot of time I've spent - holding my youngest brother, when he was a baby, on my lap, playing the organ because I could pass away the time doing that, that was much easier
 than working. And he would go off to sleep but I would still be playing - the organ and mother come
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 When your brothers were coming along, how did - who looked after mother then, did your granny come?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Grandma used to come up - Mondays and go bac
k - Wednesdays - until - my - my sister and I got - big enough to do - things. But time I was eighteen, nineteen my mother was in failing - health, then. She was taken with - whooping cough - it turned to consumption. Whereas in these days it would have -
 been cured. And from then - on, I was - I was doing the baking, bread, cakes, seedy cake, brown bread, making butter, working ever since I can remember nearly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did any of the family ever go fishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I don't think they were very good fishermen. R
eally. My - oldest brother wanted to - go out - in a boat, and he - thought he'd like to go out - in a boat down Porthleven one day, we were down there for the afternoon - and he went out and when he come back he was looking like a ghost so I think that f
inished his fishing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you yourself take part in any sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
I didn't used - no sports, I used to go in for - showing, you know, for the - shows a lot. 'Cos we used to have a - when - when I was about sixteen - the - war was on then you was hav
ing local shows for the Red Cross, I used to go in a lot for - showing, used to do - bread and cakes and sponges and - butter and used to do very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Won prizes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, won prizes, lot - well - I never - generally - come in the running - for bre
ad and yeast cake and - that kind of thing, butter, used to do - butter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And the Royal Cornwall Show?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
I never went to the Royal Cornwall Show not to - Christmas Shows, fat stock shows for bread and cake, I - used to enter there, but I never went
 to the - Royal Cornwall show. Because it was such a - way to - carry your produce for - if you didn't have proper transport see. We didn't have not motor car. Then - any - anywhere's went with the horse and cart or else the horse and trap, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did it ever take place anywhere near to your home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
The Royal Cornwall Show - has been into Helston, when we were small, but we didn't go. Then - You couldn't - well you couldn't afford to go, not - mother and father with - children really. Somebody had to
 stay home - look after the small ones and - mother was generally the one to stay home.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was it possible to go to any theatres in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I never went to a theatre - until I got - thirty - thirty-five or six I suppose. No. Never went pictures. Then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Pictures in Helston were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 There was pictures in Helston. But I never went to the pictures. Couldn't afford the money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Concerts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, any concerts around. And lots of times I've come out - from concerts before it finishe
d because - you must be in by nine o'clock. Lots of times I've come out. Used to be great time then for revival services, you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you go to those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, we used to go to those. If they was - nearby. Yes. And - quite amused in a lot of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You used to have conversions?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes, that was the - amusing part.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You felt it was more amusing, you didn't feel it was a thing to take part in yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 It was - it was funny sometimes. I remember Bishop - Hunkin's father, he was 
a coal-merchant in Truro, and he was a great Evangelical man, he was at Carleen carrying on a mission and he - oh went to visiting all the neighbouring places around, he came up to our place one - Sunday, to see us. And I can remember his prayers as well 
as anything. My three brothers were there, and he prayed that they should all be - preachers and father said lend them the horse and trap to drive around. I thought that was the funniest thing - to pray for.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 This was in chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. And there was
 another one - revival service at a little place called Crowntown, the chapels gone down now. And that man - he made some noise at that. My father could hear him - from over our place when he was - shouting and bawling. So -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What was this little place called?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Crowntown. Yes. That's between - no, between Nancegollan and Sithney that - the chapel there, Bible Christian chapel - they're Free United Methodists.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did any of your friends believe in this Evangelical work then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well I don't know whether they believed in it but they - it was the thing to - to - go - then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Everybody else did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes. That - that was the thing to go, there was - chapel was the interest - the - their social work and everything was - at - from the chapel, th
ere was - wasn't anything else going around anywhere. Band of Hope, that was the great thing then. Used to get up concerts, and - go off giving concerts - to different places around about.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Other chapels?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Used to go all over the place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You used to sing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you do anything else, recite?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Sing, recite I did - and dialogues.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Sketches?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 When you were still a school child did your parents give you any pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I don't remember having p
ocket money, but used to have an ha'penny - quite often - from an old man that used to live down the road. Quite often he'd come out in the mornings and give us an ha'penny each, and - we - to go to school we went through a croft - and there was - a littl
e
 shop out to Crowntown, and you could have a big packet of sweets for a ha'penny then. Oh lots of times - he was quite generous, they used to say he was - mean, but - with we children, my sister and I, he was quite often he'd come out in the morning and g
ive us that ha'penny. Well that - a ha'penny was a fine thing then. But when we got fourteen used to have sixpence a week pocket money. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What did you manage to spend that on?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I've gone to tea treat - and because my sister wouldn't spend - an
y money I wouldn't and I've gone to tea treat and come home again and haven't spent a penny. We used to - have a - penn'orth of sweets quite often over in the village if we went to a shop there, have a penn'orth of sweets. Always had - bought a penn'orth 
of sweets Good Fridays because the - Mrs Ward always kept shop - open Good Fridays and we always had penn 'orth of sweets Good Fridays. You had - all sorts - to pick from then. Great packet full.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You saying about the Helston Harvest Fair, you didn't save up money to spend on outings like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well we used to have - a bit extra when we went to Harvest Fair. But then you see father and they would always be buying plums, you didn't want to buy - plums or fruit because they would be - they bought the
m, and - you would have a few sweets that's all that there was - to buy - to buy in.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They'd have a sweet stall?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Harry Perry a man called called Harry Perry kept the stall - under the town clock. He used to have it - Saturdays and Harvest Fa
ir and any fair days. And in the evening time it was one of these old - oil lamps hanging from the stalls sizzling out - with - a flare - flaring out, and he used to make his own rock. And it was three ha'pence a quarter pound. So we always had a quarter 
pound of - rock. Yes. Homemade, cinnamon, lovely rock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What other sort of stalls did they have at the harvest fair then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well - you know, tin whistles that kind of thing, the small toys and - sweets and rock, fruit, that - more - there was no clo
thing, not like it is - in - the fairs today. No clothing like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You said about ponies coming down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes, to - they used to have - scores of ponies used to come down from up on Dartmoor and that - and then - farmers were bringing their bulloc
ks, extra bullocks they'd move in, walking in from - Lizard. And miles around, to market, yes, leaving home early in the morning, four or five o'clock to go all the way to Helston. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Harvest Fair would be on a Monday always?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes, yes, al
ways on a Monday. People come - well you'd see them once a year, meet your friends. And they used to - go in and have a - cooked dinner in the restaurant that - that day. Yes. Wouldn't dream of it any other time.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 That was the one red letter day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
That was the red letter day. I remember having - bought - a red astrakhan coat-one harvest fair, and a black velvet hat. And I was always outsize. My clothes were always - cost more than my sister's because - I was so big. And she used to get quite annoy
ed because my clothes cost more than hers.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 That was your winter clothes would be bought then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
That was my winter - winter coats and hats, yes. Because you always wore they Harvest Festival, when Harvest - Harvest Festivals come on. After - Harve
st Fair. Sometimes - if the weather was - had been good, you finished cutting corn the Harvest Fair and sometimes - I can remember being wet they hadn't cut a sheaf, then that - that would make - with the short days coming in, make it - a lot harder work 
for harvesting. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Some call it plum fair didn't they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes. Because - oh plums used to come down from Aversham there, and the fruiterer - there was one man in par - I think he had the run of the - show really, Eathornes. Used to have great stal
l there, top of Methodist steps. Every sort and kind of fruit - growing there, all out in the open.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And the Ram Buck Fair at Wendron, what time of the year was that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 That's in - July.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 The summer?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. The second or - fourth Saturday quite often.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 That's where they used to have the donkey races?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
That's where they had the donkey races. And - horse - there was horse racing too there. That's about the only place I remember hearing there - there was horse racing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was there any betting on that sort of thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I expect there was. I daresay there's a - little bet or two put on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 None of your family would be interested in that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. Goodness.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did anyone outside the home help your mother look after her house or family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. Nobody.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. Relations if they came - would -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Just grandma?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes. Grandma, and then - one time my father was in bed for - typhoid fever, and my mother - was in bed with diphtheria, at the same time. Well you
 didn't go hospital then. We used to have - a man come three days a week to help my father. And my auntie was home from Bodmin - then, and she was up - looking after us and doing the household work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 That's the auntie who was a nurse?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes, yes, she was there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 She's the one who helped with the sewing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, she's the one used to help - help sewing, yes. She used to make our dresses and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 With diphtheria in those days did you have to have your place isolated or could you still send your milk and things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 We didn't used to hear so much about - isolation then, no. No, we didn't hear so much about - isolation then. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 If mother was ill or confined to bed how did she manage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well I'd stay home from school sometimes - when she was - poorly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And when the young children were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well they were all born at home. A - auntie came up - from Penzance - when - the second boys was born. Grandma was there when the first boy was born, and auntie Janie came when - the 
second boy was born, and - my auntie from Penzance when the third boy was born. But then she didn't stay very long because I was - going on for fifteen then. So I - I was the - cook wash - maid and - all, dairy maid and all, general.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did your parents have family friends to come round visiting?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. That was nothing new for people to - turn up, come for a cup of tea you know. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Casually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Casually, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Without special invitations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes, People used to like to come I think because - we always had plenty of cream you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Made welcome?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes. Yes, I think they were. Made welcome and - the pork butcher, he always used to - have his dinner at our place every - Wednesday. And sometimes his wife would meet him there
, bring an hot pasty, to him there, well then she would stay for the afternoon 'til he'd finished his round and he'd pick her up - in the evening about five o'clock. So that was an outing for her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did mother and father share the same friends, they'd be family friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Fam - family friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Friends would be invited into the house if they called?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, and quite often - after - thrashing days - come over in the evening a bit to have a bit of - roast beef you see. That. Yes, special, 
yes, yes, special time, goodness. There was some baking done - on thrashing days. To get ready, all the - beef. So we used to have a - a - round of beef, pin-round of beef, about twenty, twenty-two or three pound and you could have it then for ten pence a
 pound. Well there was a lovely piece left - after thrashing day you see and that used to be lovely come over to have - harvest supper. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They had a special harvest supper?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Only after thrashing, they would come over - in the evening, come over in the evening a bit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Have a bit of a sing-song?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Come in and see what the corn run like. Boiled puddings and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 There'd be other farmers?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And their wives?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, yes. Well every - used to help one another. Then. All help one another.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Thrash at one place one week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And another place another day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Another - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 There'd be a visiting thrashing machine would there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 There was two or three in - in the - area, some - when we were small 
they used to be pulled with horses - there. Four horses in the - engine, four horses in the middle part and - and one horse in the baler. And that was some thing to see the thrashing machine. You - people used to go from place to place - to see the thrash
i
ng machine pulled in, to see these horses pulling in - the thrashing machine. And then the man would come again in the morning - that was going to stoke up the engine, he would be there three o'clock in the morning to get - the boiler up and - all - good 
coal and get the fire - going to get the - working order for the - eight o'clock. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Get the steam up?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Get the steam up, yes. Then when it got a bit later it was - pulling by tractors but - in - when we were children it was always horses.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They'd go from farm to farm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Go - yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Would it all be done in one day or several days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
In the beginning - we used to have - two days thrashing, one in the spring and one in the autumn. And then the war came on and - you was compelled to -
 grow more and it would be three days perhaps - then to start with. And if it happened to be wet weather you'd have they men around - for a whole week perhaps, to feed-before you could do the thrashing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You couldn't do it until it was dry?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, 
you couldn't do it - no, couldn't do it until there was a dry day, well - there was some preparation - to - for the cooking and that. And when the war was on, well it - you didn't know what to get really, some - started then people making pasties for thra
s
hing. Well men didn't like pasties very much - after being accustomed to having roast beef. Some people made rabbit pie, well that was worse than ever. I know - lots of times we've made fowl pie, well that wasn't too bad, we've killed fowls and - made fow
l pies for thrashing. But - rabbit pie - that - there used to be some complaints about - if they had rabbit pie anywhere. They could never get a man to go - thrashing there if he had a rabbit, thinking he was going to have rabbit pie.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What would they have to drink at the thrashing the men?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
We used to make cocoa and tea. But - 'course we were teetotallers see, but in a lot - some places they would have barley beer, well that was - liked quite a lot - that was something that was but ours was cocoa o
r tea. Carry a great - market baskets of - food and they would eat - goodness I don't know wherever they put the - put it too. There was a - like a good feed in croust times. Leaving alone their dinners and teas.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did they sit around at the harvest field to have them or come to the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
When - they were - we carried croust out in the harvest field when we were cutting corn and hay and that then, but they always came in to dinner, hot dinner. Came inside for - for our - corn carrying or anything 
like that they always came in to dinner but - in thrashing time - they always came in to dinner but I carried croust out in the barn - for - middle of the day and - even at night after they finished. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 People often tell us in those days they made t
heir own amusements, I know you always had the music, were there any other ways that friends and neighbours would get together in the spare time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well I think - if you was assoc - associated with chapel - you see, you had your concerts, Band of Hope 
concerts there. I think that - I don't think we ever - I can remember any - concerts in barns. Like -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 A barn dance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No barn dances nor nothing like that. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Many people divide society into different social classes or groups, in that time b
efore 1918 did you think some people belonged to one class and some to another, were there any different ones in your locality?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well I did - we didn't mix with any different ones, I don't know I suppose they were - would have been - different - clas
ses. The people that had the money. Was in a different class to the - people that were - working hard to - make their living. They would - mix more. 'Cos they had their carriages and - horses to go in then didn't they. Then. I suppose they were -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Can you think of any that were different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well they used to have their parties at Trevarne.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 That's at the Bickford Smith's?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, and Clowance - and - and Godolphin, they had their parties there was - their Christmas parties especially, they used to have there.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Who lived at Clowance?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
The - St. Aubyns. The St Aubyns living at Clowance then. And then there was - the Pendarves's down here, and the Bickford Smiths down there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They kept house of servants in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes, the Bickford Smiths did, yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 So there would be the working class which would embrace most everybody in the village?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes. It would. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And then just these people and their estates?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. They would have - their own class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another, were you ever told to curtsey to anyone?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, I didn't - be in that class, because - we never - went out to - work under anybody like that. Now, my
 auntie - went out as parlour-maid - one auntie did, went out as a parlour-maid, well - she was different to what we was, she was always - bow and - nod to the - society, but - I wouldn't - because I was - I remember when I was going to school we used to 
t
hink - the girl - the children that came to school and their parents were working in Trevarno - well they had to - bow to Trevarno. But - we didn't because - we didn't work for them. But when you got older it wasn't the people - the people themselves that
 the - the society themselves didn't wish that kind of thing really did they.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was there anyone that you called sir or madam when you were a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well Mrs Bickford Smith used to come - down to the - school, we always had to say good morning mad
am. And she came with the - long - her dresses down to her - ankles, you know, black silk down to her ankles and - her - lornarette or - up to her eye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you see any of the rest of the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Oh we was continually seeing 'em, they mixed with people - there. Yes, we see them - quite often.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did they come to your chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
No, Trevarno. Chynale chapel then you see they was - was where they were interested in. Nancegollan was just a little hamlet I suppose, there was nobody - very wealthy around there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Do you remember anyone showing respect to your parents in these ways, calling them sir and madam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. They were respected. And - thought well of, but not - sir or madam, no. And - father was asked advice and - for a lot of things.
 And give - recommendations and - different people who wanted to go away or anything. And I had a letter - from a man - in America, oh not so long ago, he had the - letter that my father gave him - when he wanted to - go on the railway. He carried it to A
merica - and he still had it with him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were any people in the village thought to be more important that anybody else?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 The only one that I - There was only one man that I can remember that was in Nancegollan - and he was a - solicitor I suppose. A
nd he owned the land - all around Nancegollan, and he - all the houses - in Nancegollan were built on the life system. My uncle and father built - grandfather - built three houses all on the life system then they fell away. And they all came back to him a
gain. And he used to keep a little shop and the people - that worked in the mines had to come there, and - change their money - for goods. He was the - big man I suppose in - of those days The chapel was built on his ground.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Why did they have to come there to buy their goods?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well, they were living on his land, you see, and he was - he would change their money from the mine.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They were tenants?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well, they were - they were on - living in his - leasing, yes, yes, that - that, kind of thing. Mr William Paul Jewell.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were shopkeepers thought to be in any social class different?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. No. They - just small shops - trying to make a living.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What about teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 The - schoolteachers? Well there were different schoolteachers around - there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 The one who lived near you, was she a farmer's daughter?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes, she was a farmer's daughter, there's two farmers - two sisters. They went school-teaching. And the stationmaster at - Nancegollan in those days, his - two of his daughters went school-teaching, one of those - taught me. There.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Would they be thought to be of a class to themselves?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, they were - they were simi - similar to you - and me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 And farmers would be on the same kind?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Same - yes, same footing. 'Cos there wasn't any - big farms - when - not around where we live.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Nothing more than a hundred acres?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. No, that was about it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 A bit less probably?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, a lot less - a lot less. A lot of people broke in - a few acres you see, of 
their own land and - working on something else, perhaps out with a horse and cart carrying on the roads and - the railway was put through in my father's time, well he worked on the railway, and like - a lot of others to - get a living more - have a wage, 
see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 There were no to her employers actually in the area than mining?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, some would work mine - some would work to mining.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 The mine-owners themselves didn't actually live in the area?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, the mine-owners were here, in Camborne, see, C.V. Thomas and they kind of people, they were - there \endash  mine-owners.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Would you say that there was any difference in the people that went to church as opposed to those who went to chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you consider that all the people in the working class had the same standard of living or were there different groups?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well, then - a - a farm - labourer - was - some were only getting ten shilling a week, and milk. That class - the farm labourer must have had a very - mean living. They could have milk and potato - ground.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did they live in farm cottages?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes, lived in farm cottages, no convenience - what - whatever. I remember - the farm joining ours. The farmer was on the Board of Guardians, Helston Board of Guardia
ns, and he would come home Saturday nights, about - be nine - ten o'clock. Say - out comes old Tommy, he throw the reins on the horse and poor old Tommy he had to - then - put away the horse and - that was all - seven days a week - there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 For ten shillings?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 For ten shillings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did they have a big family then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, they had - well they'd several children. He was one of ten himself, the old man.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you feel that any group felt themselves superior to the rest? For example to these farm labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well I think the - farmers - thought they were - better than the farm labourer - one up from the farm labourer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Financially?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, financially and - he was there for that purpose, to work, that - that was his job.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were some families thought of as rough and others as respectable?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well we had a few - was proper drunkards. Round about. There. They weren't particular then - some were rough. There was illegitimate children being born then, same as there is now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was there any distinction between craftsmen and labourers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
No, well the carpenters in they days - had to serve five years apprenticeship. They went for - a shilling the first week. First year. Shilling a year. Shilling a week for the first week. Two shil
ling second year. Three shilling third. Four shilling fourth, five shilling, for the fifth year. Five shilling a week. And - my husband's - mother - was a widow and she had - three - children - to raise, and two boys went to learn - their carpentership.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did she have a farm or smallholding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
No. No, no, her husband died in - Africa, and she was left with three children. Her father - lost his leg in - in the mine, when he was a youngster, and then he went - and learnt to be a tailor. He was - tailor
ing, he had tailors shop over in Nancegollan. I remember going into see him with my father when I was a little girl and he was in the bed, and he only had a wood leg after that, after he - had his leg taken off. Cut off - in the mine - he was crushed - in
 
the - in the mine, and it was cut off there and then. He survived and went - and - went and learnt the tailoring trade. And - he used to make suits for people round about and - had another - go down to Godolphin Cross - two or three days a week, to - work
ed and - tailoring, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Do you remember anyone being described as a real gentleman or a real lady?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well I think we had the opinion that - anybody that was - upright, honest, and would do anything for anybody else - was a - a lady. Not because they had money and that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was it possible at that time if you were in one class to move from one class or group to another? Do you know anyone who did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well I known some girls that were out in service - that made good and got in good positions, you
 know, worked theirselves up and got in good positions. Went away to London. I think you had to - you had to go away from village life - to - progress in anything - like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 It wasn't possible if you stayed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well there was no outlook, not for 
anybody staying, you had to go away from - home like - different ones did, they had to go abroad, a lot of people did in they days because there was no employment here for them, and - go away to the big towns to make anything - for themselves. Yes. And th
en they'd come back with different ideas and -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Do you remember seeing a policeman around where you lived as a child?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, a policeman came to the door once - and when he saw me, he said, look at her, she's scared out of her life. We had been to 
Nancegollan station and dropped our bicycles there and - went to Camborne, and when we were gone there was a bicycle lamp stolen - from - the station, and so this policeman came to the door to see if we had seen anybody or know anything about it. And when
 he saw me - my dear, I was frightened. Policeman come. I think that's about the only time I ever saw a policeman.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 If you were naughty did your mother ever say I'll call a policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. No. If we were naughty we had a - clout.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 She didn't need to call a policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How do you think the police got on with the people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Oh I think the police got on very well with the people. In - that district. There wasn't the - anything - really very - bad, the village policeman - didn't have a very hard - job, not - then I don't think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You said your home was rented, did you see anything of your landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Oh yes, our landlord lived quite nearby. We used to think it was nice, we used to go down there - after her husband died we - my
 sister and I used to go down there Saturday evening. She was glad for us to come to have company, and we used to think that was lovely to go down there, she'd always make - coffee or cocoa or something for us before we went back.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What sort of home did she have?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
She had a very nice - she had a farm - it was a farmhouse, but - it was a very nice - house, quite modern for - those days. Big kitchen. Nice fire - there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did she have any family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 She didn't have any family, but she had a niec
e, her husbands niece used to come and her husband's niece was our Sunday school teacher, and - she used to go too Saturday nights and - she was glad to have our company too, because she was - her father had died and she was on her own. But - every Saturd
ay night - she used to go there, we didn't always go every Saturday night, but quite often used to go down there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What were they like as landlords?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They didn't spend - any money - in - doing up - your house, you had to do that yourself. And it w
as quite a job to get - anything - repaired. And then when the - war came on - I suppose - well, must have been after the war, she - she sold it then. To father. Well he had to take out the mortgage on it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Do you remember feeling your parents had a struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well they worked hard to make ends meet. They would never - have a thing unless they could pay for it. They always had the money in their hand, and when the monthly accounts from the mill or anything like that was due, pay it. You know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Do you ever remember your father being ill?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 He had - he had - oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 He had typhoid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 He had typhoid, yes. And - when we were small - I remember - the old loft - had you climbed up over a ladder straight against the wall to 
get up in this loft, and there was no door there, it was an open space, and he fell down this here - ladder one day, and was knocked unconscious. And - our neighbours only lived a - few yards down in the road, but my sister and I were sent down there in t
he evening time, quite dim, to get Mr Mewton to come up, and we said, come quick 'cos our daddy have fallen down the ladder. But - it wasn't - he was in bed for a day or two, but not -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 He was never ill long enough to make much difference to the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. No. Not then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Do you ever remember anyone in the neighbourhood getting help from the Guardians or the Parish or any sort of charity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well there was - the poor house they used to call them into - Helston. People - used to go I know. An
d have relief, what they - what they would get. Some children used to come to school, used to have to have boots - from - the Parish Council.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did they have to wear big heavy boots in those days, those children?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, they did, wear - wear heavy boots. Well they were - most of the boys wore hobnail boots in they days.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 With the roads bad you'd need them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Do you remember anyone in the district whom the people disapproved of strongly being made to leave by rough music or dru
mmed out or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, I don't remember anything like that. No, not in - our district, I think we were quite - it was quite a quiet place really.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were you given lessons by either of your parents before you went to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, 
because I went to school when I was two and a half. And from that time on you come home and - recite or tell what - you learnt at school, what you'd done - there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What time in the morning did you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Went away about half past eight - in the morning, carried our dinner with us. And got home - half past four.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 This was a board school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes. The - board school. And there was a - a milk factory down at Chynale at that time, and our father used to carry milk one time down there, to this milk 
factory. And then after the milk factory closed they had this great pond - up there by the milk factory, and we children used to go up there and sit down and wash our feet - in the pond, in the dinnertimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Near the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How did you normally get to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Walked.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How long would it take you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 About - took us about a half hour - get to school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Who went with you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well these teachers that lived near - in the next farm, they took us when we were small. When we got old enough we'd go by ourselves.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You used to take your midday meal with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 We'd take our mid meal - midday meal with us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 It would be sandwiches or pasties would it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Sometimes we've - come home part way, mother come to meet
 us with a pasty. Come part way home from school and she'd come out through the croft to meet us, with a pasty.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Eat it on the way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What did you think of school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I used to like going to school. We used to have - nature study days.
 And they days we would - take our pencils and books and go down around Trevarno gardens. Used to think that was lovely, to go down Trevarno gardens and go around. With our pen and pencil. And I had a boyfriend when I was going to school. Got engaged real
l
y, yes. We used to bring chocolate to me nearly every day, and I sat up one end and he sat the other and time he passed it down to me - there was a small portion got to my end. And I was - going to be Crowntown tea treat, and he and his cousin and a - ano
t
her girl and me, we were going to get engaged and - got up to the stall and we'd picked out our ring. Mine was a tuppeny ring and hers was a penny ring. And then the boys fell out afterwards, one said - oh, you couldn't afford to buy but a penny ring, I b
ought a tuppenny ring - for my girl. Then I had a sixpence given me, for taking another little girl to - going to school, well a sixpence was something - then, my goodness, yes, I had sixpence
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How did you feel about the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I though - I thi
nk I - I liked our teachers. We had a mistress - when I went to school, there was a mistress there when I went to school first, but - there was some rough boys there and it got that she - couldn't manage them and then there was a master sent. And there us
e
d to be a whipper in - then, this old man, he had a paralysed arm and he used to drive - a horse and trap. And he let this - used to tie the - horse out to a gate, and the chute opposite the school, and - one - while he was in school - talking to the mist
r
ess one day, these great boys - took this horse and trap - and went off for a ride. And they went miles. Miles they went with this horse and trap, when they come back this old horse was sweating, and there's this poor old fellow - waiting, and he said, no
w
 I know you're good boys, I know you're good boys, but don't do that again - for me. But after that they had a - a master, because - and when master came, I saw him - once I saw him take a boy and strap him to the seat, and give him a good - lancing with 
the cane, another boy - he - was going to give him on the hand, and he cut a wart clean off. But - they quieted down after a master came there.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What misdemeanours would they have done to be punished in that way then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well they - cheeky or - or s
omething, I can't - I was - I wasn't old enough to remember what they done. But I - I saw the - what the results was and I know the oldest sister to the boy had left school, and - she had - her father had lent this cane - to the mistress that was there. A
nd this - oldest sister came in and she said - Mr Hart - I'll have that cane. She said, that came from our house. So Mr Hart never had a cane no more after that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Would girls be punished in the same way as boys for anything they did?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I - no, I don
't think girls was. I can remember - I was always very fond of talking, I can remember that teacher catching me on the arm and - pinching me hard for talking. I could always talk pretty well at school. No, we used to have our photograph taken periodically
 - at school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You'd got them still?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, got - well - some things still in there, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did the teachers emphasise certain things as important in life, for example, manners?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Manners. And one teacher was - oh she was some strict on 
your sewing. If it wasn't done it - nice stitches, out it had to come again and - being redone. Yes, she was very strict on sewing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Tidiness?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, laid emphasis on read - on writing. Yes, you had - writing was studied a lot - then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What about punctuality?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well you were - supposed to be in school by nine o'clock. You were told off if you was - after that, unless you had some good reason. For that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did they emphasise certain ways of speaking?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Oh I think we were - had to be - 
manners, that was - that was emphasised, good manners, that was - emphasised then, when anybody come in - rise. If any of the governors came around you always rose in your seat. And when the - Mrs Bickford Smith come down you always said, good morning mad
am, or good afternoon, whenever - it was.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You don't remember any of the other governors?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Oh yes, one was a Mr Adams, he used to come around. But - we always rose when he come in - when he came in, but we didn't - say good morning sir because he was only a farmer up the road, but - he used to come in and look around sometimes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were your parents interested in your school work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They asked you what you did at school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. We had - had to bring home our - work to show - what 
you was doing, sewing or anything like that, you bring it home to - show what you were doing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did they visit the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I don't remember my mother - ever coming to the school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did they meet the teachers socially or outside?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, I don
't think so. They - the two teachers - lived - on our doorstep nearly. And - parents didn't come into school - then to see their - children. A lot of parents had small children at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did the other children come from similar types of home to your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, I think they did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did the teachers ever single out some children for different treatment from the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I don't remember - them - any one particular child being singled out. Like they are now, some were - brighter than others.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were any children left out of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, I don't think so. Not - in our class - they weren't.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Do you remember any gangs or groups in the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Not in they days - we didn't have any gangs or groups - there, we had - our different amu
sements I think, used to group together to - play different things. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 These boys that went off in the trap, they wouldn't normally be a gang?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, they just - three or four of them and they decided they're going off with this - trap, well that was lovely weather you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How old were you when you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Fourteen. I should like to have gone on - to school - a bit longer, but I went to dairy school then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 The dairy school that you spoke of, did your parents have to pay for you to of there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. It was County Council - was - running that - at the time. That was up in the old milk factory.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Who were the teachers there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Had a - a Miss Nicholls - and her sister. There was only two of them come. And there was one gi
rl came from Lizard, there you know, and Mrs - Mrs Bickford - Smith, not - the old lady that was a governor but her - daughter-in-law, she came and took these courses as well. There.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Could anybody go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes, you could go there. There were two
 - two course - two sets of courses, those who - that were - over twenty, and those that have - from fourteen to - yes, school leavers from fourteen 'til -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What subjects did they teach?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Oh, only \endash  butter-making. That's all. Then - then they had 
a - quite modern equipment in those days, different to what we had at home, they had lovely churns and small churns and - butter workers and - you - made it in grains first of all to get a different - than you were doing then. You could - learnt to do fan
cy patterns and - make all sorts of things, and cream and cheese and - oh it was - it was very nice if you liked it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did it help you?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. It helped me to - the way - to - make it - different to what you did in - yes - to what - yes - to what you did at home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How long did you go to that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Had three - three courses - at that, my father - eight, nine weeks at a course then I think. Half - just half a day, every half day - there then. Adults'd be in a - afternoons and - school leavers in the mornings.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 So that the three courses would last altogether about -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well several - several months. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 About nine weeks a course?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, yes. Yes. Several - several months.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Then you would do your work at home in the other part of the day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you have any regrets about your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well at that time you didn't think nothing about it. But it's since - when you got older, you wish - that it seems that my life was - planned out - for me, because see when I go
t nineteen my mother was ill, and - twenty-one and she was dead, well - I was the oldest and - I had no intention when I was sixteen or seventeen of staying - at home, or here anyhow. I - had every intention of moving away. But I couldn't make up my mind 
to do it then because my youngest brother, he can't remember his mother at all. And - I stayed at home and - then I married and - still stayed at home. Living with five men one time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You had a lot to do then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Used to get up four o'clock in the mo
rning Mondays - to get on with washing and butter-making in the summertime. And I used to do a lot of potting butter - in the summertime. Used to have pots brought from Scilly Isles, Hayle, Helston, Whitlam. People used to - pot butter then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They would come for the butter when it was potted?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, when it's potted, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Do you think you benefited from attending school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Oh yes, certainly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 While you were at school did you have any part time job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Except at home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Minding the baby.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 When you left school from then on you actually worked at home on the farm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes. Yes. Do all sorts of things. My mother and father both went to school. Was - sent to school, yes, used to be tuppence a week. I think father did - one time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They would have gone to what they called dame schools?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes, that's right, yes. But my mother went to Leedsdown school. That was the - council - county school then, council school. Higher - higher school at one time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Would you have preferred another type of occupation to farming?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes, I should have liked to have gone nursing. And I had a - I had a type of voice - that - could have done with training. But there was never no money. I was only one out the family that had - any - 
ability that way, but - couldn't afford - to - have any money, yes, because we had to pay the mortgage off on the - place, couldn't afford to have any money spent -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You joined the Helston Choral Society?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. I joined the Helston Choral Society.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 After leaving school you continued to live at home and to work on the farm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Mm.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did this change anything at all at home, your relationship with your parents or your brothers and sisters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. They took it for granted I was there - and
 twelve months after my mother died my - younger sister got married, she left home. And then my three brothers and father was home, then I got married and - my husband was home.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You continued your weekly routine the same, Sunday just the same?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Just the same. Just the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Chapel and Sunday school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Chapel and Sunday school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you yourself take any interest in politics?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, I can't say I took interest, I always put in my vote. But I've never had - time to - study thes
e things, I don't know whether anybody's - much better off.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You continued to spend your spare time in a similar way after you left school, with your chapel and choral society?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. And chor - join - joined - joined the choral society, used to - 
cycle into Helston, that's about three miles. And sometimes - some others down the road you'd drive horse and trap and - then you'd ride.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You'd go there of an evening?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was there any other - ,
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Any - any concerts that was around - used to go - there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you make any new friends, boys or girls, at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No. Well you got to - know people, you know, mixing in the choral society you got to know - different people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you bring new friends home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well anybody you got friendly with always came home.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Welcomed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes, and then - the war came - these wars you see, we used to write to - all the boys - that was - away, and send them - oh - like - saffron buns and - food and that to - help them out a bit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you have any special friends at this time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Oh - friends of old I think. And what friends I've made I've kept them. All - the time. You know, lifelong friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did your parents expect to know where you were if you went out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Oh yes. Yes. They expect to know, they didn't always know but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did - you have to be home by a certain time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Oh - nine o'clock was the rule. I know once I was out with a - my sister and I, out with two boys. Well she was going with this boy properly and 
he brought on this other one for me you see and he put his clock back - his watch back a hour. And when we come up the road - 'cos we wouldn't - one wouldn't go in without the other. We'd always wait for one another, when we come up the road - coming up t
h
e road some father up there in the din with his shirt sleeves walking up, and my sister in some stew. She said, Bessie, do you know what time it is? Well I said so - boy put his clock - watch back. Father said to him, I think my son it's time for you to b
e going home. I think it was ten o'clock then, it should have been nine o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Where did they come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They came from Lowetown, used to walk. Walk up and walk back, after chapel.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How far away was that then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Three miles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They were farmers as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, they were farmers. Fathers sons, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What about this young lad who thought he was engaged to you at school, was he still in the neighbourhood?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, he was still in the neighbourhood.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 He was a farmer as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, he's not - he went with Bickford-Smith's - ICI.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 When you left school your first job and your only job was working on the farm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Oh - home working on the farm with my - parents.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Could you tell me roughly the jobs you had to do on the farm?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well it seems we had to do all sorts of jobs. It was out to milk in the mornings. Feed the calves, feed the fowls, wash out separator. Then - go in and help mother Do the dishes, bring water, bring coal. And then there was - Saturdays - cle
aning the slab. Blacklead. Brasso.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 This was 1915 wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes. About then. And after breakfast quite often I had to do the dishes and - father be calling, put them cows - a minute, or else, help me to change the bullocks, there was always called upon - for outdoors - to do something or other - there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Neither of your brothers were old enough to help?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, they - no, they weren't old enough to help after the war. And then one went to - drive the - equipment - to drive horse and wagon, p
icking - or collecting cream.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were all days alike or did you have a half day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
I don't remember having any half time, was generally - at home, because - there was always smaller children to look after in your spare time. And after my youngest bro
ther was born my mother's - health - started to fail. She went on a year or two but - never in good health. And time I got nineteen she was really - really sick. Then she was home for two years - with - tuberculosis.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Would you have been paid a wage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Used to have sixpence a week pocket money. Sometimes we would spend that and sometimes - couldn't afford to spend that. Save it up - for something bigger you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What about clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 We always had plenty of clothes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Mother would see to those?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes. Yes, always had plenty of clothes. Yes, Sunday - always had best clothes for Sundays. You wouldn't dream of wearing your - best clothes to town. They was kept for Sundays.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was it usual for farmers to employ their children on that basis in those days?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, yes, in those days - they were expected to - work. Some I think had more pocket money than others.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you ever earn a wage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, I never - never earned a wage. We didn't in those days. Not even the boys. They were 
working and then when they - were old enough to get married they might be set up - had a bit give to them then, you know, cow or two or something when farming but - boys or girls didn't have much - wages in - my time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What about when they got married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well - if they - their farmer - if they were big farmers - they were well set on. But if they was a small farmer, well they - would have perhaps a cow or two given to them and then - help their - work theirselves up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Start in a small way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Start - start in a small way and - careful and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were any other people employed by your father?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 My father had a man - three days a week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How did you get on with him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Oh very quiet man, he always used to come in to dinner. Very quite 
man. But he could never work with horses. He'd just do - cart work, you know, with the horse and cart but not to go out to plough or anything like that, he could - never do anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Could he milk then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well he didn't - he didn't used to milk. He would come about eight o'clock. Because we were doing the milk, we were there to milk.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did your sister Eva work on the farm as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How about the harvesters, the threshing machine men, were they local men?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well they 
used to - he - all the neighbours around helped one another. There might be a odd man or two that you would hire, but - generally the farmers around - would - help one another, then you pay that back - when they were threshing.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You were saying that some had to stay with you once because they couldn't stay at the hotel.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They weren't local people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, they were - people that was with the thrashing machine, the - went with the set of thrashing machines. Generally three men went with
 that. They go from place to place.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How would they be paid, in the set or individually?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
They would be paid - by the - lump sum for the thrashing machine. Then the man the thrashing machine belonged to would pay - they - men you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They were employed by him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, they were employed by him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you like the work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
We never thought anything about it I think. There it was. I don't think we ever questioned it. Expected it. Harvest time, thrashing days. That was the thing, you didn't question.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
You were saying about farm labourers being so poorly paid, do you remember how their children were turned out at school? Were they less well clad than the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well they were really. I know the - farm labourer down the road he 
never used to have more than ten shilling - a week, milk - and potatoes. Potato ground. And they used to say his wife - quite often would be off on the roads and leave a basin of bread and milk home for his dinner, then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Where would she go on her own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Oh, go off home to her - see mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 The old man who was kind to the children and gave you the ha'penny, what was his family background, did he have a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 He had one daughter. This old man went to America years ago - and he made money
 and he put it in the sinking fund, and he came home and he had - a little place down to Moffatss Corner, milked three cows and kept a donkey. And he had one daughter. And - in time - he was taken - ill. Mentally and physically. And he died and the - wi -
 
wife was left with this one daughter. The donkey, and three cows. And they couldn't take this money, only the interest - of this money, so invested - all they could have was the interest of this money. Well the old lady couldn't keep on the cows and my fa
t
her bought - the cows - from her. And - the donkey - she sold, she sold it one night - one afternoon, when the daughter was gone away. And I had to go down there to sleep with her, for company. And unexpectedly the daughter turned up, and found out the do
nkey was sold - and there was - a - proper row. I came down on the stairs, I said, I'm not going to stay down here, I'm going home. But she was very - daughter was very annoyed because - mother sold the donkey.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did the daughter get married then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
The daughter was - marr - got married, and - her husband was never allowed to come home - for - a good many years. But in the end he came home, and - the old lady died, and I had the - When the old lady died - she left me the gold chain - that her husband
 had brought home from America, and my sister had the watch. And another thing, when - we had holidays, I remember walking up to - Releath, about two miles from our place, early in the morning, to ride around with - Mr Mildren the pork butcher, in his hor
s
e and wagon. Used to go down to Crowan Churchtown, Praze, Horsedowns, Leedstown, Townsend, Kirthern-Wood, Godolphin Cross and back through Carleen and then drop me off up to the gate. And quite often I was told keep my tongue quiet. 'Cos he was having spe
c
ial bits - hid away up in front, and people would come out, have you got - a bit of - loin or anything nice today Mr Midlren? No, I'm sorry, I've sold it, and I used to say, piece up here Mr Mildren. And he'd say - when - when he got in again, now look, y
o
u must - mustn't tell everything that you can see. So you had to keep quiet. And we used to visit granny in the holiday time, down to Trenwheal. Go off with our - clean aprons, white pinafores - then, all starched. I think it was about a mile and a half f
r
om our place down granny's. Granny lived in a little thatch cottage. When she was younger she used to milk the cow at home, and then when she got older the cows was brought up to our place. And she used to get her - water from a well up top of the garden.
 
And it was the only place I've ever seen she always kept a nice white cloth down over her - stair carpet or - matting whatever it was there, washed and ironed every week. And her slab shining, brasses. Scrubbed, the back kitchen - had an earth floor, and 
that was sanded. There was a - in grandma's house there was a door at the bottom of the stairs. That was kept shut, quite often, quite often the cat - if it was open the cat would walk up and then her white cloth would be spoilt.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was granny an easy person to talk to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes, I think she was quite - quite easy to talk to. But she used to - granny, I remember granny got very vexed - when she couldn't get a bon - a black bonnet to wear again. She always - for best always wore a black bonnet with a fall
 down behind - here, and - the time came when they went out of date and she had to have a hat. And she's very annoyed - 'cos she couldn't have a black bonnet again. And she used - I never remember her wearing anything but black. And - a bit of white aroun
d her neck, what she used to call her tucker, and she used to have to have a clean tucker put in every week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did many people wear black like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well nearly all people, all elderly people wore black, or we thought they were elderly. But - when 
they died - some of them weren't very old then. Long - black dresses - down to their ankles.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 To go back to that dairy school that you went to, how did you go, did you have to apply to go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 We were asked - from school if we would like to attend th
is - dairy school, and we gave in our names, they that liked to go gave their names down that they would attend to this course, I think you had to have so many before they could get - the teacher to come. This Miss Nicholls from Truro, she lodged there in
 - one of the farms. They came - from all - around, some came from - as far as the Lizard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Were they all farmers daughters?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 No, they weren't all farmers daughters, some thought they would like to do it. Well even Mrs - Bickford Smith at that time
 came, and - learnt to make butter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you like it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Yes. It was interesting, because it was - you were doing different and they had different utensils to work with, were butter workers and little small churns, our churn at home was so big it wa
s really hard work. But at the dairy school, there was just little small churns. Which was - much more interesting, and we learnt to make - fancy butter, with leaves and flowers and - all - that kind of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How did you feel about the teachers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 They were very - she was very nice. There was two teachers, they were - they were really - experts I suppose in their - butter making.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 It was about this time that you had your bicycle was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 When we had our bicycle - I was - sixteen. And we 
used to go off - well quite regular to Penzance biking. And I can remember - the first time I came down over the stairs with me hair up. And my mother was very annoyed, I had to go up and take it down again. You're not going off dressed up like that.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Sixteen. Yes. And - I - when I got down in the road - I took out a motor veil and tied my hat down with motor - with a veil over my hat, so - to - went off biking like that, thought I was quite grown up. Because I'd put me hair
 - hair up under me hat again by that time. And we used to bike to Stithians, and that was up the - hill and nearly all the way to Stithians, easier coming home. One morning - one - one Christmas I biked to Stithians - to be up there - biked to Four Lanes
 to be up there in time for the carol service, six o'clock in the - Christmas morning.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 What was the attraction at Stithians then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well my - when my sister got married - she went to Stithians to live. And - we used to bike to - Stithians quite often - then.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 That was after the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. That was after the war.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 This time during the war when you had your bicycle, did you make any new friends, boys or girls at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Well we went off in groups more then. Of evenings, cycled down so far as Porthleven. Praa Sands. Have a - dip - in the sea.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 These were local people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Local, yes, the - the boys and girls who - all - all around about, we nearly all of us had bicycles the same time. There.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you have any special friends at this time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well my sister and I always - kept together mostly. But there was - some porters over to Nancegollan station then lodging, they used to lodge in the area, and they were - they - they were the attraction too. We used to - go off biking.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did your parents meet these friends?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well they knew - knew them all round, yes. But when we had spare time, see set out pick blackberries, in the summertime for - making jam. Blackberry tarts. Blackberry jelly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you belong to any organizations apart from the church? Red Cross or anything like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 I was in the Red Cross when - I got - about seventeen I went in the Red Cross up there for a spell. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 That was near your home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Sithney. Sithney Red Cross.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did your sister join it as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
No, my sister didn't. And we used to have - shows then, for Red Cross - under the Red Cross, local shows you know, competitions and - butter - cookery and that kind of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 You learnt first aid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Did you do any war work with the Red Cross?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
No. Because I was home - in the - my war work was - helping outside. Harvest time. Picking potatoes, dropping potatoes. Going to mill. That used to be twice a week, go down to mill. Carry the corn down one da
y. Have it ground, bring it back - and got to go down again - with another lot of corn and bring back what you carried down before. I didn't used to like that very much. Sometimes we'd meet these - traction engines coming - with the bins, coal, and - and 
t
he horse wouldn't - like to pass them. I remember once I - stopping this old - a man on the road, I said, here will you get up here and drive past this - traction engine with me, I don't think our horse Silver do like this - horse - this traction engine v
e
ry much. So he got up in the cart with me and - faced this - traction engine and - past it, then he got down and went back again. And we used to go out to pick potatoes, drop potatoes - broadly, and then all the - for the sending of it away we would carry
 
it to Nancegollan station, horse and wagon you - be over there - sometimes six o'clock, queued up waiting for - a train or a truck to load your potatoes - in. Might be over there hours waiting. But everything that you had then went off by train. Now the -
 line is - all gone, there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Was Mr Angove at Nancegollan at this time, did you know him at this time?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 
Well I'd known him ever since - I can remember, seems to me. But - he was - yes, well then he - when times was bad he went away to - America wh
en he was nineteen. I don't think he was nineteen. And he joined up - when the war came up he joined up in the Canadian Army, and came - to - was sent across to France. Then after the first war he was - when he was demobbed he went - different places to w
ork. Scotland, Ireland, and went back to Canada again. And when he came the - second time - when he was home for a little while we got married.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid3367464 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 That was after the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid1587792 BA  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15482063\charrsid348800 Yes, that was after the war then, yes.
\par }}